<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CSEA members vote to accept contract  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Pending Legislative approval, workers in New
York's largest state employee union will soon be working under
contract for the first time in more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Civil Service Employees Association members voted 44,245 to
2,478 to approve the new contract to replace the one that expired
April 1, 1999, the union announced Friday. The union represents
about 77,000 state workers.
</P>
<P>
   The state Legislature must also approve the contract before it
can take effect. Lawmakers traditionally approve contracts
negotiated and approved by Gov. George Pataki and unions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this sends a message across the state to every
politician in every town and village that CSEA members are alive
and well and strong in their union,'' said CSEA president Danny
Donohue. ''Not only did they stand up for their rights, but they
got a contract that was fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract gives workers across-the-board wage increases of 3
percent retroactive to October 1999, 3 percent effective April 2000
and 3.5 percent in both April 2001 and April 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The contract also has provisions to eliminate the 3 percent
yearly pension contribution for state employees who have worked 10
years or more. All workers will receive a $500 bonus and workers
with more than 24 years experience will get pension credits based
on how long they've held their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The incentives mean workers with more than 10 years service will
receive a 22 percent increase in salary over the life of the pact.
</P>
<P>
   Union members and Pataki's negotiators reached a tentative
agreement on the new contract in March to end a year of bitterness.
Union members contended Pataki was showing little respect for them
with his administration's contract offers.
</P>
<P>
   CSEA, often joined by members of another contract-less public
employee union, the Public Employees Federation, picketed Pataki at
numerous public appearances over the past year both in New York and
in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Also possibly fueling the resentment of CSEA members during the
contract impasse was the fact the union's leadership had endorsed
Pataki for re-election in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a fair contract that recognizes the contributions of
our CSEA employees and protects the taxpayers,'' Pataki said Friday
in a statement released by his office. ''This contract positions
our employees and the state well for the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue also called the new contract fair, although he said it
should have come earlier and included more.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's an old axiom about what labor really wants is more ...
clearly we would have liked more, but this is a fair contract,'' he
said. ''When you get 44,000 people saying yes and only 2,000 saying
no, I think that says something.''
</P>
<P>
   CSEA's mainly blue-collar state workers rejected by a
9,251-17,194 margin the first tentative contract agreement their
negotiators made with the state in March 1999. That contract would
have raised wages by 11 percent over four years.
</P>
<P>
   Workers represented by PEF, New York's second-largest public
employees union, are still without a contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
