<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton and Giuliani courting Independence Party  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton and her
cancer-stricken Senate rival, Rudolph Giuliani, planned to court
support today from the New York arm of the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday, it had been unclear if the first lady would attend
the Independence Party forum in Buffalo. The mayor had earlier
announced his intention to attend and reiterated that even after
announcing Thursday that he had prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon's forum amounts to a job interview with
Independence Party leaders who will select their Senate candidate
in late May or early June at their state convention.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton has been concerned that having the
Independence Party Senate line could put her on a ticket headed by
conservative Pat Buchanan, a leading contender for the Reform
Party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a problem with Mr. Buchanan,'' the first lady said
Wednesday during a campaign stop in western New York.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has expressed similar concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the last-minute decision to attend the forum,
Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said Friday that
''Hillary is determined to travel around the state and talk with as
many people as possible about why she is running for the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Clinton is also concerned about being linked with
Lenora Fulani, a leader of the left-wing New Alliance Party who is
now a major force in New York's Independence Party.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the attraction of third-party nominations is strong
in New York when candidates expect a close race. Polls show the
Clinton-Giuliani race is just that. Unlike other states, New York
allows major party candidates to also run on third-party ballot
lines and combine their vote totals.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Republican George Pataki beat Democratic incumbent
Mario Cuomo in the governor's race on the strength of the
Conservative Party vote.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Independence Party became New York's third
largest political party. As of March 1, it had more than 172,471
members. The Conservative Party fell into fourth place with 171,496
members. Both are dwarfed by the Democratic (4.96 million members)
and the Republican (3.09 million members) parties.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the line brought more than 109,000 extra votes to
Democrat Charles Schumer as he beat Republican incumbent Alfonse
D'Amato in the U.S. Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has said he will decide within a few weeks, after
consulting with his doctors about treatment options, whether to
continue with his Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Independence Party is in the midst of turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, a state judge reinstated Jack Essenberg as
the state party chairman, ruling that he had been ousted illegally
by Fulani's faction and other party leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Essenberg said Friday that while the Senate forum had been
arranged by his opponents in the party and he would not be
attending, he was encouraging other party members and the
prospective candidates to attend.
</P>
<P>
   But Essenberg made it clear that he also wanted nothing to do
with Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would rather have the (presidential ballot) line blank than
have Buchanan,'' Essenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Fulani is backing Buchanan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
