<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Upbeat Giuliani campaign trail  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- In his first campaign appearance
since revealing he has prostate cancer, an upbeat Rudolph Giuliani
says he ''wants to be senator'' but needs to determine treatment
before making a decision on his Senate candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully I'll be able to do that and run and give you the
kind of candidate you deserve.'' Giuliani told about 1,000 upstate
voters at a dinner Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City mayor was greeted with standing ovations and
cheers a the $50-a-plate event hosted by the Saratoga County
Women's Republican Club.
</P>
<P>
   At a brief question and answer session before the event,
Giuliani said he ''needs a little more than a day and a half''
before he could make any decision on the race against first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton. The mayor announced his cancer diagnosis on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I need the next week, 10 days, maybe two weeks, to figure out
the proper course of treatment. I'm going to do that and than I'm
going to make a decision and whether I can or cannot campaign,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked who he would support if he decides not to run,
Giuliani said, ''I'm not going to get into that. I know who I don't
want to support.''
</P>
<P>
   During his speech, Giuliani drew laughter when he joked about
being mayor in the heavily Democratic New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm in a state of confusion. I've never seen so many
Republicans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While not mentioning his opponent by name, Giuliani again
attacked the Clinton administration in his speech, charging the
president's claim of a successful bomb attack against Iraq late in
1998 over Saddam Hussein's refusal to conduct weapons inspection
was a ''Clintonian victory.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Clintonian words do not mean what they say,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani referred to declining crime rates and increased job
growth his crime-fighting record and the city's job growth in
recent years, saying he's elected senator, he would bring those
qualities to the state.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor, who had previously criticized Mrs. Clinton as a
carpetbagger, said, ''I want to be a senator because I was born in
this state, because I worked for the state.''
</P>
<P>
   State Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, also at the event,
said he's ''confident that (Giuliani) will do what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no second choice,'' Bruno said. ''He overcame
obstacles and he will overcome whatever life brings him.''
</P>
<P>
   After hearing Giuliani's speech, Beth Liebich, former chairwoman
of the Republican Committee in Clifton Park, said the mayor is
''magnificent.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He is enthusiastic and ready to go forward,'' Liebich said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, Giuliani made a brief appearance at New York
City Hall, where he received a gift of get-well cannolis fresh from
a Staten Island bakery. City Councilman James Oddo, R-S.I., told
Giuliani that ''my mother is setting record laps on the rosary on
your behalf.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani took a bite of the cannoli and posed for pictures
during the public hearing. ''The cannolis look great,'' Giuliani
said. ''Cannolis cure everything.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, the mayor, who has received hundreds of
calls from well-wishers, returned many -- including one to Yankees
Manager Joe Torre, who had surgery for prostate cancer last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you hear the word cancer, it's frightening. It's still
frightening, but cancer is no longer a death sentence. That has to
be first and foremost in your mind,'' Torre said later during a
pre-game media availability at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He said the mayor seemed in good spirits, and that the only
advice Torre offered Giuliani was that he should listen to his
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he will cut some of his campaign stops to make
time for consultation with doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cancel about half and do about half and that'll give me the
time to do this properly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The first cancellations were two speeches before lawyers' groups
scheduled for Monday -- one in Syracuse, the other in Rochester --
commemorating Law Day. Both were originally set up as part of
Giuliani's mayoral duties, not his Senate campaign, a spokeswoman
said.
</P>
<P>
   A scheduled stop today in Buffalo where Giuliani will court the
support of the Independence Party will proceed as planned, aides
said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's campaign spokesman said the first lady will also
attend the event hosted by New York's arm of the Reform Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
