</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- More than 200 shipwrecked Haitians rescued in a
dangerous nighttime mission by the U.S. Coast Guard arrived in Nassau Friday,
with many saying they had been trying to reach Florida. They were among 288 boat
people, many weakened or unconscious from exposure and dehydration, stranded on
a deserted Bahamian island. The Haitians, discovered Wednesday night, were from
the biggest group of boat people to reach the Bahamas in years. Rescuers found
two bodies, and survivors said 17 others either drowned or died of dehydration
during the trip, Bahama officials said.
</P>
