<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum of Modern Art employees go on strike  </HEADLINE>
By LUKAS I. ALPERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP)-- The usually contemplative atmosphere that
surrounds the Museum of Modern Art was shaken as staff members
picketed, chanted and blew whistles in front of the building after
voting to strike.
</P>
<P>
   The Professional and Administrative Staff Association, which is
a local of the United Auto Workers union, voted 115-25 Friday
morning to authorize the strike after working for six months
without a contract, union official Scott Sommer said.
</P>
<P>
   The strike is the first at the museum since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 100 employees picketed in front of the museum and
the gift shop, blowing whistles whenever anybody walked in, handing
out fliers and asking people to go to the Guggenheim or Whitney
museums instead.
</P>
<P>
   Local 2110, which represents 250 of the 650 museum employees,
includes archivists, conservators, curatorial staff, librarians,
registrars and salespeople. The union met with members of the
museum's negotiating staff for the last time on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We made concessions, and the museum did not budge,'' said John
Alexander, a five-year museum employee, as he walked the picket.
</P>
<P>
   The union says that museum salaries are too low, starting at
$17,000, with a median salary of $29,000. Another major sticking
point is job security during the period of the museum's $650
million expansion, which will begin in 2001. The museum has planned
for staff reductions during that time.
</P>
<P>
   The union also accuses the museum of trying to bust up the union
through pressure tactics against union supporters.
</P>
<P>
   But the museum's chief labor negotiator painted a different
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe this strike is about a change in the union. The UAW
is not prepared to deal with an open-shop policy without mandatory
union membership,'' Robert Batterman said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum says its latest contract offer amounts to a 3 percent
wage and minimum salary increase each year for the next three
years, an improved pension plan and a comprehensive severance
package for any employees laid off during the museum's expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are satisfied that our wages are fully comparable and
within the appropriate scale for museums in America,'' Batterman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 250 employees in the union, Batterman said somewhere
between 50 and 100 of them returned to work Friday.
</P>
<P>
   When shown a copy of the contract offer given to reporters,
Local 2110 President Maida Rosenstein angrily said that the figures
were a ''total lie.''
</P>
<P>
   The strike drew a mixed reaction from visitors, with some
continuing on their way into the museum and others refusing to
cross the picket line.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am terribly sympathetic,'' said Pierre Epstein, a museum
member for 20 years. ''This is an elitist institution which
underpays their employees.''
</P>
<P>
   No new negotiations were scheduled, and union members said they
planned to strike every day until an agreement is reached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-29-00 0102 </TRAILER>
