<DOCNO> APW20000429.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sumo Grappling With Scandal  </HEADLINE>
By GINNY PARKER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Like many men his age, Hiroshi Okuda has been a
sumo fan all his life.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up playing with paper sumo wrestlers, followed the
tournaments on television and just a few months ago -- at age 56 --
finally saw a bout in person for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sumo is an easy sport to understand,'' Okuda said, slurping
stew in a restaurant specializing in ''chanko nabe,'' the sumo
wrestler's traditional soupy fare of tofu, meat and vegetables.
''Sometimes, you'll see a small guy beat a big one -- there's
nothing the Japanese like more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone shares his devotion.
</P>
<P>
   A nagging scandal over alleged bout-fixing was back in the
headlines this week, and sumo has come under fire for being sexist.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts see a deeper dilemma: Is the very emphasis on
tradition that aficionados say makes sumo a part of Japan's soul
pulling it out of touch with the nation's modern realities?
</P>
<P>
   With roots in the religious rituals of Japan's Shinto faith,
sumo has never been just a sport. Before a bout, wrestlers toss
fistfuls of salt to purify the ring and shove their feet into the
dirt to squash any demons that may be lurking below.
</P>
<P>
   But sumo's claim on purity has taken a beating since former
wrestler Keisuke Itai set off a media frenzy in January by
announcing that many bouts had been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Itai, who retired in 1991, said he intentionally threw bouts and
named top wrestlers he said were on the winning side.
</P>
<P>
   The Japan Sumo Association, the professional sport's
ultra-conservative ruling body, investigated the allegations and
denied them this week. Officials said they questioned all those
Itai identified and found no evidence to support his allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We found nothing to back up what he said,'' said Tokitsukaze,
the sumo association chairman and a former wrestler.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, the allegations do not seem to bother die-hard
fans as much as they have angered the general public. They are, in
fact, almost considered part of the package.
</P>
<P>
   The way sumo tournaments and rankings work is a big factor, said
Ryohei Nakamura, editor of Ozumo, a popular sumo magazine.
Wrestlers are ranked according to their cumulative record after
each of the six, 15-day tournaments each year.
</P>
<P>
   If a wrestler is one bout away from demotion in the closing
days, it hasn't generally been seen as such a bad thing for an
opponent to let him win, or for the favor to be returned sometime
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ''Customs and traditions like this continue because sumo, in a
sense, is still a traditional Japanese art,'' Nakamura said. ''It's
part of the charm.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that bout-rigging has become an issue may be more
significant than the allegations themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Proud of its ancient roots, sumo has tended to hold itself aloof
from the changes that have dramatically transformed the rest of
Japanese society -- and its values -- over the past several decades.
</P>
<P>
   The sumo association does little to promote the sport, and has
kept its internal affairs closed to all but a select group of
former wrestlers granted the privilege of opening their own
training stables. Only wrestlers from these sanctioned stables are
allowed to compete.
</P>
<P>
   The spartan, communal life in those stables is bleak.
</P>
<P>
   Wrestlers toil virtually every day through rigorous training
regimes. Injuries are common. For those who do not make the top
ranks, pay is meager. With Japan's modern affluence providing far
more options to athletic youngsters, few are willing to accept such
hardships.
</P>
<P>
   Nakamura and other other sumo experts warn that if something
isn't done to open the sumo world, these factors will likely
further alienate the public and cut off the flow of competitive
talent the sport needs to survive.
</P>
<P>
   ''Go to the tournaments and you see empty seats,'' Nakamura
said. ''That didn't used to be the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Young fans in particular are growing hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's so out-of-date,'' said Tomoko Matsumoto, a 25-year-old
office worker in Tokyo. ''It's something for grandmothers and
grandfathers to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, meanwhile, a movement aimed at bringing sumo into the
modern world -- by getting it into the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   With little help from the more powerful professional ranks,
supporters of amateur sumo have been trying for years to build up
enough of a worldwide following to get an Olympics berth.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting tradition is not their major concern. Amateur
wrestlers are allowed to wear shorts underneath their loincloths,
and are even promoting sumo for women.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the professionals were embroiled in a controversy
earlier this year over their ban on women in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Sumo officials have long refused to allow women in the ring for
any reason, because the ring is considered sacred ground and Shinto
belief holds that women are impure.
</P>
<P>
   But Fusae Ota, Japan's first female governor, said in February
that she wanted to present an award to the winner of a local
tournament. The association said she wasn't welcome and Ota ended
up sending a man to present the award.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 0121 </TRAILER>
