<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Coalition Wins Confidence Vote  </HEADLINE>
By ELLEN KNICKMEYER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Having survived an essential test of parliamentary
support, a stopgap coalition led by new Premier Giuliano Amato is
pledging to devote its short run to reforming a fractious electoral
system that has given Italy 58 governments since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   The 58th, Amato's 4-day-old government, won a vote of confidence
Friday in Parliament's lower house by a surprisingly comfortable
margin -- staving off, for now, early general elections demanded by
conservative opposition leader Silvio Berlusconi.
</P>
<P>
   ''Reform of the electoral system is one of the reasons this
government was born,'' Walter Veltroni of the coalition's leading
Democratic Left party declared after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   When that reform is achieved, Veltroni said, Italy can hope for
a future in which ''governments are decided by the citizens, and
which have the possibility to govern with stability for the entire
run of Parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   What is now an eight-party center-left coalition came to power
in 1996 elections. It managed to stay on despite infighting that
helped bring down its previous two premiers. The last premier,
ex-Communist Massimo D'Alema, resigned after the conservatives made
a strong showing in April 16 regional elections.
</P>
<P>
   Amato, D'Alema's treasury minister, took over, reshuffled the
Cabinet, and urged lawmakers to let his new government stay in
power until next spring's scheduled elections.
</P>
<P>
   The center-left argued its leadership was essential to seeing
through election reforms, starting with a May referendum giving
voters the choice of doing away with a proportional allotment
system for seats in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The system is blamed for giving disproportionate influence to
tiny, troublesome parties -- currently, there are more than 40
parties in Parliament. The profusion makes for unwieldy coalitions
that are easily toppled.
</P>
<P>
   The extent to which even Italians are accustomed to the rise and
fall of their governments could be seen in TV's handling of the
crucial vote of confidence. TV stations didn't cut in to announce
the vote -- even those that had their evening news shows airing at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Amato managed to persuade his allies to stay
together. Friday's vote was a convincing 319-298, with five
abstentions -- broader than the razor-thin margin that had been
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Defeat would have brought down the fledgling government. While
it still faces a vote of confidence in the Senate next week, the
margin there is expected to be wider.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is good news, because now we can go ahead with the
referendum,'' Franco Bassanini, the new government's public
administration minister, said after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi made clear that Amato's government would face plenty
of trouble from him, denouncing the prime minister as the
''bankrupt caretaker of a moribund majority.''
</P>
<P>
   The media magnate and ex-premier had contended that the
coalition's poor showing in the regional elections represented a
voter mandate for early elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''The day isn't far off in which the citizens, using the vote
that you fear so much, will take back the power to decide, which
you have for so long held hostage,'' Berlusconi warned the
center-left just before Friday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   However, Amato's chief danger in the lower chamber had been
defections among followers disgruntled over the distribution of
Cabinet secretary and undersecretary seats.
</P>
<P>
   He won over wavering supporters in part by coming through on a
pledge they had sought to purge voter lists of the dead, a padding
that helped doom previous reform referendums, by making it more
difficult to get a quorum of qualified voters.
</P>
<P>
   Amato first served as premier for 10 months in the early 1990s,
earning respect for rigorous budget cuts at a time when corruption
scandals were pulling apart Italy's political order. Detractors see
him as a remnant of the system that produced the scandals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 0123 </TRAILER>
