<HEADLINE> Balaguer Could Lead Dominican Rep.  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNAH A. NESMITH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- Joaquin Balaguer is 93
years old, blind, barely able to walk and reviled by many
Dominicans as a symbol of a repressive past. And he might be the
country's next president.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign is remarkable for how little he says. Balaguer's
public appearances are carefully orchestrated events at which aides
physically support him as he delivers simple, stock messages about
''putting Dominicans first'' -- a thinly veiled nod to many
Dominicans' dislike and fear of the large migrant community from
neighboring Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't come here with a bag of promises. I will govern as I
always governed,'' he said in an unwavering voice at a recent rally
in a poor Santo Domingo neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   With three weeks to go before the elections, Balaguer is running
even with Danilo Medina, the candidate of the governing Dominican
Liberation Party. Balaguer and Medina, a centrist, are widely
expected to unite in a second round of voting against leftist
leader and current front-runner Hipolito Mejia.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the alliance: Balaguer's support was critical to
getting the Liberation Party's Leonel Fernandez elected president
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Balaguer's Social Christian Reformist Party promises a return to
the days when a paternalistic state kept everything from crime to
the price of gasoline under control. His proposals include
reinstating trade barriers, government housing projects and massive
public works projects.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign slogan: ''One more time, by necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   That would make it his seventh term as president.
</P>
<P>
   Balaguer was a top lieutenant to Rafael Trujillo, the country's
dictator from 1930 until his assassination in 1961. After the
assassination, Balaguer was briefly exiled, only to return in 1965
and win election as president a year later.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected president twice more before being forced by
international pressure to concede defeat and order the military to
return stolen ballot boxes in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   He won again in 1986 and was re-elected in 1990. Claims that his
1994 election victory was rigged forced him to shorten his term.
</P>
<P>
   Balaguer's amazing longevity seems to have his rivals somewhat
spooked -- and many Dominicans fascinated.
</P>
<P>
   ''Balaguer has been converted into a political myth,'' explained
sociologist Teofilio Barreiro. ''He's the man who can bring order
to the disorder.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Liberation party candidate, Medina is running on the
record of President Fernandez -- generally respected for reducing
rampant corruption and inefficiency and carrying out economic
reforms. Because of a law inspired by Balaguer's disputed 1994
election, Fernandez cannot seek a consecutive term in office.
</P>
<P>
   Many Dominicans, however, remain frustrated by poverty, even as
Santo Domingo is transformed by construction of highways and the
economy grows by 8 percent a year -- the fastest growth rate in the
Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Mejia's calls for creating jobs through huge public works has
wide appeal -- even though his Dominican Revolutionary Party is
remembered for extraordinary corruption during its last term in
power two decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Most polls show Mejia with 40 percent to 50 percent support with
Medina and Balaguer splitting the rest. If no candidate gets an
absolute majority -- as appears likely -- a second round is held
between the two top finishers.
</P>
<P>
   Some find the idea of Balaguer returning tough to stomach.
</P>
<P>
   It ''verges on the ridiculous,'' complained Senate President
Ramon Albuquerque of the Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Balaguer is treated with kid gloves by rivals aware of his
potential kingmaker role.
</P>
<P>
   ''The two parties are being coquettish with the old man,''
Barreiro said. ''They visit him. They speak well of him. They can't
afford to risk angering him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 0125 </TRAILER>
