<DOCNO> APW20000429.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies 12, Mets 5  </HEADLINE>
By AARON J. LOPEZ, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Mike Piazza left because of wrist and elbow
injuries in the fifth inning and Mets starter Mike Hampton was
chased moments later as the Colorado Rockies beat New York 12-5
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza is expected to be out of the lineup for at least a few
days. The All-Star catcher sprained his right wrist and
hyperextended his right elbow in a play at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ''The diagnosis right now is we're going to lose him for some
days, there's no doubt about that,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine
said.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who played through a thumb injury during New York's
playoff run last year, was taken to Rose Medical Center for X-rays,
which were negative.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza returned to the clubhouse after the game with his wrist
wrapped. He said he did not know how long he might be sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   ''Immediately, I felt some pain in my wrist,'' Piazza said.
''Initially, I thought it was going to be OK. I tried to shake it
off, but it was pretty persistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza was hurt as Todd Helton scored on an errant throw from
second baseman Edgardo Alfonzo during a play at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ''He just slid into me. I felt some tenderness in my wrist and
elbow,'' Piazza said. ''The next couple of days will tell how it
feels. From my experience with sprains, usually if they're severe
they get worse in the first couple of days. If not, maybe it will
be feeling a little bit better. We'll just wait and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Valentine: ''He hardly ever comes out, so there's something
there. We're hoping for the least.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who have lost three straight after a nine-game winning
streak, trailed 6-0 when Piazza left. They never recovered as
Hampton (2-4) equaled his loss total from all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The runner-up in last year's NL Cy Young Award voting, Hampton
has struggled to measure up to last year's standards when he went
22-4 with a 2.90 ERA for the Houston Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to be New York's ace after an offseason trade, the
left-hander has allowed 24 earned runs with 30 walks in six starts
covering 33 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies tagged him for seven runs, six of them earned, and
eight hits in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you're facing a guy like Hampton, you're always hoping
that you score enough because he's going to battle you on every
at-bat and every pitch,'' Rockies manager Buddy Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Helton broke out of a 1-for-15 slump with three hits, and
Jeff Cirillo drove in three runs for the Rockies. Colorado batted
around twice, scoring six runs in the third and four in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Astacio (2-2), making his first start in nine days, gave
up five runs and 12 hits in 6 2-3 innings. The Mets finished him
with five straight two-out hits to cut Colorado's lead to 11-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies, playing only their eighth home game, never trailed
as they took a 6-0 lead in the third on the strength of two walks
and five straight hits off Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   After Hampton walked Brian Hunter and Mike Lansing, Larry Walker
capped an 11-pitch at-bat with a two-run triple into right-center
field. Cirillo, Helton and Jeffrey Hammonds added RBI hits, and
Brent Mayne hit a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Walker finished 3-for-4 and scored twice.
Notes: Hampton had been 4-0 at Coors Field. ... Colorado RHP Jerry
Dipoto was placed on the 15-day DL and is scheduled to have surgery
next week to repair a bulging disc below his neck. The Rockies
recalled Mike DeJean from Triple-A Colorado Springs. ... RHP Eric
Cammack made his major league debut for the Mets. He gave up four
runs and four hits in two innings. ... Astacio made his first start
since April 19. His scheduled start Monday was rained out, and he
did not travel with the team to Montreal because he did not want to
risk visa problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
