<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> School Hosts National Dream Hotline  </HEADLINE>
By DOUG JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINDYVILLE, Mo. (AP) -- Sometimes we fly, other times we fall.
Often we're being chased by wild animals or monsters. And even more
frequently, we're naked.
</P>
<P>
   Each night, we might have as many as six or seven dreams. But
for those of us lucky enough to remember even one of them, the big
question is: ''What does it mean?''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Condron, chancellor of the School of Metaphysics, will
tell you. This weekend, Condron and others at the school's campus
will be running their 12th annual National Dream Hotline.
</P>
<P>
   Through midnight Sunday, people can call the school and describe
their wildest, weirdest or most entertaining dreams. Faculty
members on the other end of the line will interpret them.
</P>
<P>
   ''The subconscious uses pictures to tell us things, that's what
dreaming is all about,'' says Condron, who has been studying dream
interpretation for more than 20 years. ''Understanding those dreams
is one path toward realizing your purpose in life and leading a
happier existence.''
</P>
<P>
   Every dream is about the dreamer, Condron says, and every dream
is unique to that person. However, there are common themes that his
''Dream Team'' hears repeatedly during their weekend dreamathon.
</P>
<P>
   Try this old favorite: The dreamer is chased by a wild animal or
a dog. Animals represent habits in dreams, and being chased by your
habits -- be it smoking or biting fingernails -- means you might be
having trouble controlling them, Condron says.
</P>
<P>
   Another typical dream is finding yourself back in high school or
college on the last day of the semester and realizing you're
unprepared for final exams.
</P>
<P>
   ''School is a place of learning. This dream is saying you have
passed up opportunities to expand yourself or to grow,'' Condron
says. ''It's also a sign that you may be living in the past and
that you need to progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Flying is a good thing, it means the dreamer is trying to get
beyond those self-imposed limitations. Death in dreams symbolize
change, and being killed might indicate that the dreamer feels
helpless about those changes.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the dreams where we bare it all.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being naked in a dream is very common, and it's usually
accompanied with a crowd of people or a public place,'' says
Condron. ''It tells us that we are being more open, perhaps too
open, about our personal lives. It's something few of us are
comfortable with, but we all need to try and be ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone dreams, but not everyone will remember, says Condron.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you want to remember your dream, you have to tell yourself
before you go to bed that you're going to remember it. Then write
them down as soon as you wake up,'' he says. ''If you can wake up
without the aid of an alarm clock, it's even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Some courses at the school are meant to help students master
skills like concentration, listening, memory recall, re-energizing
and relaxing of mind and body. There are four students enrolled
full-time at the school's headquarters, located on 1,500 acres of
rolling hills near this tiny Ozarks village. They raise their own
food, churn their own butter and lead a self-sustaining life on
campus.
</P>
<P>
   One of those students, 25-year-old Greg Brown, of Manhattan,
Kan., said he enrolled two years ago to help himself sort out his
own recurring nightmares and to try to learn something about
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''I used to have this dream over and over that I was being
chased by wild animals or by people with guns,'' said Brown. ''Now
I dream of flying. I have really come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   The campus, which is not affiliated with any college accrediting
group, began in 1968 as a series of classes in Springfield. It
became an incorporated, nonprofit school in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a hippie commune, it's just a school of like-minded
people who want to better themselves,'' staff member Paul Blosser
said. ''We are offering something different from the traditional
ideas of school.''
</P>
<P>
   Condron says his staff and faculty provide the dream hot line as
a kind of community service. After that, he says, it's up to the
dreamer to decide what to do with that information.
</P>
<P>
   ''They will assist you in understanding the images in your
dreams, and you, the dreamer, will be the final authority in
applying the information in your life,'' he says.
------
</P>
<P>
   The National Dream Hotline can be reached at (417) 345-8411.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.som.org/dreams/ndh--info2000.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
