<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 9th driver killed, NYPD steps up efforts  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hours after the ninth livery cab driver was
found murdered, police Commissioner Howard Safir assigned more
officers to the same task: protect the other 41,000 drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven livery drivers were killed in 1999. Fernando Mateo,
president of the New York State Federation of Taxi Drivers, met
with Safir Friday for about 30 minutes to discuss the drivers'
safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 300 officers are on the task force. Safir didn't give
any numbers but promised a ''substantial'' number of extra cops to
watch over the drivers, Mateo said after the meeting, which was
closed to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Safir showed Mateo a video about the livery cab industry that
will be delivered to all precincts. Among the video's reminders for
cops: All cabs in the city have amber warning headlights they can
flash if they are in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ''We spoke about the flashing lights and how a lot of police
officers are not acknowledging that the flashing lights are on ...
it's what signals when a livery driver is in trouble,'' Mateo said.
</P>
<P>
   He added no cabbies who complained their signals were ignored
have been harmed.
</P>
<P>
   Also, police will set up more checkpoints where they stop
drivers to see if they're OK, and task force officers would work
longer hours and patrols would increase. The FBI has been asked by
Mateo's group to assist the NYPD. FBI spokesman Jim Margolin said
no federal statutes have been violated and there is no jurisdiction
for the agency to intervene. But the agency will provide assistance
if requested, he added.
</P>
<P>
   In separate appeals, Safir and Mateo begged livery drivers not
to pick up street fares, a practice that is against Taxi and
Limousine Commission rules. All but one of the slain drivers were
killed by street fares, police have said.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the extra few dollars, your life isn't worth it,'' Mateo
said.
</P>
<P>
   The latest driver slain, Cesar Lopez, 43, of Staten Island, was
allegedly killed by one of two passengers picked up in Brooklyn at
3:55 a.m. Friday, police said. Lopez, a native of the Dominican
Republic, had been a livery driver for 12 years, working the past
five for Livonia Car Service. He is survived by his wife and three
young children.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a nice person, always laughing, always joking around,''
said colleague Julio Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   Like the cars of the eight drivers killed before him, Lopez's
car was not equipped with a bulletproof partition, police said. In
response to the killings, the TLC voted last week to require all
drivers to install either bulletproof partitions or digital
security cameras in their cars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the TLC made it mandatory for yellow cabs and livery
cars owned by more than one driver to have the partitions. But cars
owned and operated by individual drivers -- 90 percent of all livery
cars -- could have either partitions or tiny surveillance cameras
installed behind the rearview mirror. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
recently pledged $5 million toward a grant program to help pay for
the security devices.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., asked for $600,000 in
federal funds to purchase 2,000 partitions.
</P>
<P>
   The recent increase in driver murders and the new requirement
has apparently overwhelmed shops that install partitions, which are
cheaper to install than cameras. Partitions cost between $250 and
$350, and cameras start at $600. The waiting list to have
partitions installed ranges from one week to two months.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why livery drivers pick up street fares, Mateo said
it was a combination of finances and understanding. Drivers can
make more money with street fares, he said. And because they live
and work in the inner city, they know the community depends on them
for transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo urged residents to come forward if they have information
on the killings. Police have made arrests in only two of the nine
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're crying for your help, we're the people who transport
you, we're the people who work for you, your parents and your
grandchildren,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Taxi and Limousine Commission: http://www.ci.nyc.ny.us/html/tlc
</P>
</TEXT>
