<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study links good day care to crime prevention  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton made a rare appearance
at the White House to take the wraps off a new study showing that
children who spend their early years in quality day care are less
likely to commit crimes later in life.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by law enforcement groups, found that youths who
spent their early years in quality day care were half as likely to
be arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ''Child care is not only a lifesaver for working families, it is
a crime-fighting strategy for our communities,'' the first lady
said Friday. ''For every dollar we invest in child care, we save $5
in crime costs down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has made child care a key issue in her U.S. Senate bid
in New York. The appearance, her first in Washington in slightly
over a month, came a day after her Republican rival New York City
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced he has a treatable form of
prostate cancer and is not sure if it will scuttle his Senate
plans.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady made no mention of the mayor in what was billed
as a non-campaign event Friday. But in a sure sign that she had
left the campaign trail, Clinton ditched her trademark black
pantsuit in favor of a one that was a bright mint green.
</P>
<P>
   She was joined at the White House by Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn., and Rep. Benjamin Cardin, D-Md. They said the report
provided fresh evidence of the need for more money for child care
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The report is a compilation of studies from North Carolina and
Chicago in which children in programs were compared with those who
weren't in programs. It found that troubled children who didn't go
to preschool or receive home visits from social workers were five
times as likely to become chronic lawbreakers -- arrested four or
more times -- by age 27. The children in the study had similar
socio-economic and family backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The report was issued by Fight Crime: Invest in Kids, a
700-member bipartisan coalition of police chiefs, sheriffs and
crime victims. Former police chiefs William Bratton, of New York
City, and Jerry Sanders, of San Diego, were among the report's
authors.
</P>
<P>
   It called for increased spending, saying for many poor families
child care consumes a quarter of their incomes.
</P>
<P>
   It also proposed better training and higher salaries for
child-care workers -- whose median hourly wage is $4.69, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, Dodd and Cardin are pushing for an additional $3
billion to create slots for another 950,000 children in Head Start
and for block grants to expand early education and child care for
kids under 5.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is also pushing a plan to provide tax breaks for
parents and employers that offer day care for workers' children.
</P>
<P>
   The report's author, Dr. T. Berry Brazelton, of Harvard
University, said ''scientific research now proves the early
childhood development programs that help kids in so many other ways
are also our most powerful weapons in the fight against youth
violence. We have every kind of evidence that this works and works
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, polls released along with the child studies
showed that parents and police alike overwhelmingly support
child-care and after-school activities.
</P>
<P>
   There was less agreement on whether children should be charged
as adults, kept in prisons or subjected to other increasingly
punitive measures, organizers said. The polls found that 17 percent
of police chiefs favor charging more juveniles as adults, compared
with 12 percent of the public.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Fight Crime: Invest in Kids:
http://www.fightcrime.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-29-00 0205 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000429.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 02:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Rescues Shipwrecked Haitians  </HEADLINE>
By JESSICA ROBERTSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Ragged and weary, 288 Haitians rescued
from a shipwreck in a dramatic U.S. Coast Guard mission have
arrived in the Bahamian capital, with many saying they were trying
to get to Florida and that up to 17 people died in the attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Crews rescued the Haitians on Thursday, with U.S. Coast Guard
helicopters evacuating 65 people suffering from severe hypothermia,
dehydration and kidney failure. Their ship ran aground Wednesday
off Flamingo Cay in the Ragged Island chain, about 250 miles from
Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   At least 22 of those hospitalized were released and placed in
detention on Friday, when the remaining passengers arrived in
Nassau aboard a Bahamian Defense Force cutter. They also have been
placed in detention and will be questioned before being sent back
home.
</P>
<P>
   ''We left Haiti in a boat because of the situation in the
country. There's a thousand riots,'' said Barnabas Estime, one of
the survivors. ''There's a lot of other persons who leave for the
same situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The boatload -- the largest single group to arrive in the Bahamas
in years -- comes amid a dramatic increase in the number of Haitians
seeking refuge here and coincides with increasing violence in Haiti
as the nation gears up for long-postponed legislative elections.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate incident, 122 Haitians landed Wednesday on Inagua,
the southernmost Bahamian island 100 miles from Haiti's north
coast. On April 21, 224 Haitians arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Some fear that the Bahamas and the United States could face a
new flood of Haitians headed for their shores.
</P>
<P>
   ''You know that election will be held in Haiti and the situation
has become harder,'' Estime said.
</P>
<P>
   The new arrivals may just be a usual increase during the Easter
season, when migrants believe there will be fewer Coast Guard
patrols, Bahamian immigration director Vernon Burrows said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ''there is major concern as to whether or not there is
going to be some mass exodus of persons out of Haiti into the
Bahamas or the United States during the next few months,'' Burrows
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, rescuers found two bodies on the
half-submerged Haitian vessel, a 50-foot wooden slope intended to
carry no more than 50 people, according to Petty Officer Gibran
Soto of the U.S. Coast Guard in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Nedly Martinborough of the Bahamas Defense Force said
survivors told him Friday that as many as 17 may have died.
Earlier, officials said survivors reported eight people had drowned
in a storm and when the boat ran aground, and another six died of
dehydration on Flamingo Cay.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately known how long the survivors were on the
cay -- a 10-foot sliver of scrub land and rocks -- without water or
food before the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   Three U.S. sailing vessels spotted the wreck and alerted
officials.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Coast Guard helicopters ran dozens of flights, ferrying
survivors and supplies flown by a C-130 aircraft from a Coast Guard
base in Clearwater, Fla. The operation ended Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Martinborough said the survivors told him the group allegedly
stole a boat and scraped up enough money for food and water and to
pay a captain to take them to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Haitian ambassador to the Bahamas, Joseph Etienne, said many
Haitian-Bahamians have called the embassy for information on those
who died, which officials have not yet been able to compile. He
said Haitian authorities have promised to step up patrols along the
coasts to avoid more potentially deadly trips.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clearly the government cannot allow the situation to worsen,''
Etienne said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
