<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lindenmuth Wins at Cycling Trials  </HEADLINE>
By TIM KORTE, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRISCO, Texas (AP) -- Tanya Lindenmuth insists she's still in the
learning stage of her cycling career. Her competitors might try to
dodge her if she gets any better.
</P>
<P>
   Lindenmuth, of Trexlertown, Pa., won the women's match sprint
Friday at the U.S. Cycling trials, beating Jennie Reed of Kirkland,
Wash., in the first two races of a best-of-three format.
</P>
<P>
   It was a rematch of last year's national title match, when
Lindenmuth took the championship from Reed, an old friend from
their training days.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the second time I've been able to be competitive
against her,'' Lindenmuth said. ''She's always been so strong and
I've admired her so much, her poise and her strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindenmuth, 20, isn't doing poorly herself. Although she and
other cyclists won't know the Olympic team until U.S. coaches fill
the roster in July, she made a strong case for herself.
</P>
<P>
   In match sprint, riders try to position themselves in the first
two laps to beat the opponent during a final-lap sprint. Strategy
comes into play when a rider tries to disrupt the other's
positioning.
</P>
<P>
   Lindenmuth won with wits and power.
</P>
<P>
   Reed started ahead of her in the decisive second sprint, setting
a rapid pace. Lindenmuth's thighs burned, but she stayed within
striking distance and then blew past Reed on the homestretch.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew after the first ride she'd want the front and she was
going hard,'' Lindenmuth said. ''And that hurt, it definitely hurt.
But it felt really good to come across the line first.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Trexlertown rider won men's sprint, but Marty Nothstein
established himself years ago as one of the world's top riders.
He's comfortable carrying most of U.S. Cycling's medal hopes for
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's not a problem for me,'' he said. ''I want the load. I
want to be the guy who's expected to win. I can race well under
pressure, and I wouldn't even call it pressure. I know what I can
do, and I know I can win.''
</P>
<P>
   In the men's sprint final, Nothstein dispatched Jeff Solt of Los
Altos Hills, Calif., in two races.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm real pleased with the way I rode,'' Nothstein said. ''I
rode with good power, with a lot of strength. But by all means,
I've got a lot of work ahead. I'm right where I want to be, but I'm
not an Olympic gold medalist yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothstein was cheered by fans who filled the stands at the
Superdrome. After beating Solt, Nothstein raised his index finger
as he crossed the finish line. On the victory lap, he raised both
arms and waved.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just part of the game,'' he explained later.
</P>
<P>
   Nothstein isn't finished yet. He is scheduled to compete in
today's keirin, where a pack of riders follows a pace motorcycle
for two kilometers. The cyclists sprint over the final two laps.
</P>
<P>
   In an exhibition event, he planned to go after the one-lap track
record.
</P>
<P>
   ''I plan on demolishing it,'' Nothstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Jame Carney, a purple-haired distance man from Flagstaff, Ariz.,
won the 25-kilometer points race. He also won the miss-and-out, a
non-Olympic race where a pack is thinned by removing the last-place
rider on each lap.
</P>
<P>
   Lucy Tyler, an Australian with dual American citizenship, won
the 20-kilometer women's points race. She's estranged from the
Australian cycling team and, training in Miami, is seeking a
release to compete for the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   In the final event, Tanya Dubnicoff of Winnipeg, Canada,
established a women's single-lap track record. She covered the
250-meter track in 14.69 seconds to beat nine other riders.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. Cycling team site: http://www.usacycling.org
</P>
<P>
   Superdrome track site: http://www.superdrome.com
</P>
</TEXT>
