<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 04:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Offers Education Plan  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore took a
record-setting four hours of questions at a town hall meeting
before making a midnight stop at a rollicking Native American
pow-wow.
</P>
<P>
   Gore apologized for arriving so late to the Gathering of
Nations, which was in the midst of a late-night dance contest, with
dancers in traditional Native American feathers and paint stomping
to the beat of pounding drums.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I start these (town hall) meetings I always say to the
people there that I will not leave as long as anyone has a question
to ask me. What I didn't understand at the beginning of this
meeting was that everyone had a question to ask me,'' Gore told the
Gathering of Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's question-and-answer session was meant for undecided
voters, although there were a good number of students too young to
vote there, too. Education dominated the discussion, with about one
in three questions focusing on schools.
</P>
<P>
   One teacher asserted that all politicians promise help for
schools yet help never seems to arrive in her classroom. Why was
Gore any different, she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Gore responded that he hoped to win the presidency with a
mandate from voters that would give his education plans momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I am entrusted with the presidency, I will have your voices
backing me up when I go to the Congress and the country and say, 'I
said this is my No. 1 priority and you elected me,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore answered questions on topics ranging from the environment
and immigrants to Elian Gonzalez and political gridlock.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed with one man that not enough gets done in Washington
but disagreed that eliminating political parties was the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Gore agreed that more money is needed for health research, but
he declined to endorse Gary Taylor's request for a huge increase on
diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   And when a man in black leather began explaining the benefits of
drug legalization, Gore shot back, ''I'm not for it,'' a response
that was met with applause from the audience and mock relief from
press aides.
</P>
<P>
   The questioner, Paul Hilliard, said he was ''happy enough'' with
Gore, who went on to discuss his support for drug abuse treatment
and other initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a politician, that's what he does,'' Hilliard said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore took questions from the audience for more than two and a
half hours. Then, for another hour and a half, he talked with
participants one-on-one. Some just wanted autographs or snapshots,
but others engaged him in extended policy discussions on a host of
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the previous record for a Gore town meeting was three
hours and 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   One man questioned him at length on his position that Elian
Gonzalez' fate should be decided by a family court that would
consider the child's best interests.
</P>
<P>
   ''The decision shouldn't be made on the basis of politics,''
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The man responded, ''If I could really believe that this had
nothing to do with the calculation of trying to win Florida I would
feel a lot better about voting for you.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Well thank you,'' Gore responded.
</P>
<P>
   Participants were pretty frank, even as they talked with the
vice president up close, one-on-one, albeit surrounding the Secret
Service officers.
</P>
<P>
   Marcela Diaz questioned Gore on immigration issues. The pair did
not agree on several points, and she told him: ''I would like to
vote for you, but I really need to think about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 0449 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000429.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 04:50 </DATE_TIME>
