<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seton Hall academic year ends with questions about unsolved dormfire  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) -- The flags at Seton Hall University no
longer fly at half-staff. The police tape surrounding Boland Hall
is long gone. Students passing each other on the college green chat
about finals, parties and dorm assignments for next year.
</P>
<P>
   But more than three months after a smoky, intense dormitory fire
killed three freshmen and injured 58, the school year is ending
with so many unanswered questions.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be nice,'' said sophomore Eric Nunez, staring at
Boland Hall, ''to know what happened, exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   Nunez most likely will go home for the summer next week without
learning the cause of the blaze that began in a third-floor lounge
before dawn on Jan. 19.
</P>
<P>
   The fire sent hundreds of terrified freshmen staggering
half-dressed into the predawn cold outside. Some jumped out
windows; at least four were critically burned. Authorities found
the bodies of Frank Caltabilota, John Giunta and Aaron Karol, all
18, in the lounge and in a nearby bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Essex County Prosecutor Donald Campolo stopped giving any public
updates about the investigation within days of the fire. Campolo
refused recently even to say how many people are still assigned to
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Fire safety experts say that because evidence is often burned
away, fire investigations can take months to complete. But the
delay worries many.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if they'll ever find a cause,'' said Edwin
Matthews, the attorney for the village of South Orange who said he
has worked on about 30 fire cases. ''Usually, you find these things
out relatively quickly if you're going to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a feeling that the cause lies in one of the kids that
died,'' said Lauren Covino, a 19-year-old freshman. She said she
does not believe that any of the victims is responsible for the
fire, but ''maybe one of them saw how it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Quoting law enforcement sources who request anonymity, The
Star-Ledger of Newark has reported that investigators are focused
on three Seton Hall students who they believe either set the blaze
or know about it.
</P>
<P>
   One of those students had admitted to vandalizing the lounge
where the fire started, but not to setting the fire, the newspaper
reported. The investigation has stalled because the suspects have
refused to grant additional police interviews, the sources told the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Campolo said the length of the investigation is not unusual, but
didn't say he was confident the fire would one day be solved.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm confident that we're doing the best we can and will
continue to do so,'' he said. ''I'm not in the business of making
predictions.''
</P>
<P>
   Campolo is a 1975 graduate of Seton Hall, a fact he calls a
''nonfactor'' in the investigation. A commuter student, he never
lived in Boland Hall as a freshman and said his attachment to the
campus hasn't made his determination to solve the case stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think I would have reacted the same way with respect to any
campus and any set of parents who lost their children this way,''
Campolo said. ''It's just a tragedy, regardless of where it
occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, Seton Hall dedicated a bell tower to commemorate the
victims of the fire -- a metal cylinder the height of a flagpole
with a cross and three bells for each student who died.
</P>
<P>
   University president Monsignor Robert Sheeran, who moved into
Boland Hall after the fire, will preside over commencement
ceremonies on May 8.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone's going forward, but there's still a very deep sense
of loss,'' said university spokeswoman Lisa Grider. ''My guess is
Commencement will be sort of bittersweet.''
</P>
<P>
   But the university still must face questions from students,
parents and state officials over its fire safety policies.
</P>
<P>
   The university acknowledged that for years it never held
organized fire drills, as required by state fire codes, because it
believed that false alarms that resulted in evacuations counted as
the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   The state Division of Fire Safety in February took over
inspection duties of the university from the South Orange Fire
Department and found hundreds of unchecked fire violations at
campus buildings. More than a dozen students and the families of
Caltabilota and Giunta have filed papers saying they intend to sue
Seton Hall for millions.
</P>
<P>
   And the lack of sprinklers in Boland Hall led to a statewide
debate on fire safety, with several lawmakers introducing bills to
require sprinklers in all college dormitories. Seton Hall has begun
installing sprinklers in all of its dorms.
</P>
<P>
   Candy Karol, the mother of victim Aaron Karol, said that parents
must take responsibility along with the universities for the safety
of their children.
</P>
<P>
   ''When a parent's going to send their child to school, you
better ask that school, do they have sprinklers,'' Karol said. ''It
never occurred to us.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why didn't I ask? It cost me my son's life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-29-00 1130 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
