<DOCNO> APW20000429.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 11:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suspect In Custody in Pa. Shootings  </HEADLINE>
By KRISTEN HAYS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The violence started at a suburban home, where
a Jewish woman had been shot dead, and quickly spread to an Indian
grocery store, a Chinese restaurant and, finally, a karate school.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of an hour, police say a man targeting
minorities calmly drove across the four Pittsburgh suburbs Friday
afternoon and methodically picked out his victims.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, five people had been shot dead. They included the
Jewish woman, a black man, two men of Asian descent and another man
of Indian descent. A second Indian man was critically wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested Richard Scott Baumhammers, 34, an immigration
lawyer and the son of Latvian immigrants who lived in suburban
Mount Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney William Difenderfer, who said he is representing
Baumhammers, answered the door this morning at the Mount Lebanon
home where the suspect lived with his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're devastated as to what happened and they are extremely
sympathetic to the victims and their families,'' Difenderfer said.
''Right now we're trying to piece things together.'' He declined
further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Baumhammers, meanwhile, remained jailed early today in Beaver
County, where he was arrested shortly after a 22-year-old black man
was shot and killed in a karate studio. He was charged with
homicide and reckless endangerment in that shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said his arraignment was pending on the other
slayings, which occurred in adjacent Allegheny County.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are taking a tack of ethnic intimidation -- a hate crime,''
said Paul Wolf, acting Allegheny County Police superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   The deadly shooting spree was the second of its kind in the
region since March, when a black man allegedly yelled racial
epithets and killed three white men.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was an attack against us all, because it sought in its
violence to divide us by the color of our skin and the nations of
our ancestors,'' Gov. Tom Ridge said from Pebble Beach, Calif.,
where he was speaking to a Republican group.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are struggling to make sense of what appears to be yet
another brutal racist rampage.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside Baumhammers' brief arraignment Friday in Beaver Falls,
about 25 miles northwest of Pittsburgh, a crowd jeered him and
called for his execution. He smirked as police led him around in a
bulletproof vest.
</P>
<P>
   The killings took place within a 20-mile range through suburbs
surrounding Pittsburgh. The shooter was armed with a .357-caliber
handgun, the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette reported today.
</P>
<P>
   Police received first word of the shootings shortly before 2
p.m., when they responded to a small fire at the home of Anita
Gordon in Mount Lebanon, next door to the home of Bauhammers'
parents. Gordon, 63, was found dead inside the home. She had been
shot twice.
</P>
<P>
   While they were at Gordon's house, police got a call of shots
fired at Beth El Congregations, a synagogue less than a mile away
where Gordon was a member. The synagogue's glass doors were shot
out, the word ''Jew'' was painted on the front and swastikas were
painted on its outside walls.
</P>
<P>
   Police then received reports of two men being shot at an Indian
grocery store in Carnegie. Anil Thakur, 31, died at Allegheny
General Hospital about four hours after he was shot. Sandip Patel,
25, was in critical condition early today at Mercy Hospital in
Pittsburgh, authorities said. The Post-Gazette said he was shot in
the neck and was facing the possibility of permanent paralysis.
Both men are of Indian descent.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Kretzler, who owns a travel agency next to the Indian
grocery, said the shooter appeared calm as he walked out of the
store, tucked away a gun and walked to his car.
</P>
<P>
   ''He got in and sat for maybe five or 10 seconds without doing
anything, and just very calm and collectedly pulled out as if
pulling out after buying a bag of groceries,'' Kretzler said.
</P>
<P>
   Shots were fired shortly afterward at another synagogue in
Carnegie.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen minutes later, police received a call reporting two
employees had been shot at a Chinese restaurant in a McKees Rocks
shopping plaza. Killed were Thao Pham, 30, a deliveryman of
Vietnamese descent, and Ji-Ye Sun, 34, the Chinese manager of the
Ya Fei Chinese Cuisine restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   About 3 p.m., police received call of man shot at karate school
in a Monaca shopping plaza. Garry Lee, 22, was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Baumhammers was arrested about 15 minutes later, after someone
at the karate school provided police with a description of a
suspect driving a black sport utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said Baumhammers had a gun and several rounds of ammunition
with him when he was stopped, and was taken into custody without
incident.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has joined the investigation because of the possibility
that the crimes were racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Baumhammers passed the Georgia bar exam in 1993 and belonged to
the Georgia Bar Association. His parents, Inese and Andrejs, are
both dentists and his father taught at the University of
Pittsburgh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 1133 </TRAILER>
