<HEADLINE> Woody Harrelson Sues Insurance Co.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Actor Woody Harrelson is suing an insurance
company he claims wrongly stopped defending him against a lawsuit
filed by two tabloid photographers.
</P>
<P>
   Harrelson filed the breach-of-contract suit against Allstate
Corp. on Thursday in Los Angeles County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from a 1996 federal civil rights suit filed by
the photographers after they scuffled with the actor at an airport
in Martha's Vineyard, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Harrelson said he tried to grab one man's camera after the man
ignored his request not to photograph his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Allstate allegedly withdrew its defense of Harrelson just before
the lawsuit went to trial in 1998. Harrelson claims Allstate
attorneys should have represented him because he had a ''deluxe
homeowner's policy'' to protect himself against personal injury
suits.
</P>
<P>
   Harrelson also claims errors by Allstate lawyers forced him to
pay about $3,000 in damages to the photographers and $80,000 in
legal fees to their attorneys. The insurer's negligence cost him an
additional $150,000 in legal fees of his own, he claims.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Dodas of the Northbrook, Ill.-based insurer said the suit is
routine and will ''stand or fall on its merits.''
</P>
</TEXT>
