<HEADLINE> Andy Dick Says He's Staying Sober  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Former ''NewsRadio'' actor Andy Dick has been
sober for nine months and he's trying to take control of his
comedic career.
</P>
<P>
   For years, he felt like he had marionette strings attached --
''you pull the string and I'll pick my nose.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was always appreciative to just let people take advantage,''
he tells US Weekly in its May 8 edition.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Dick pleaded guilty to charges of possessing cocaine
and marijuana after a May 15 car crash in which he toppled a
utility pole near the Hollywood Bowl. He also pleaded no contest to
charges of driving under the influence and hit-and-run.
</P>
<P>
   But now he's eager to rebuild his reputation -- and career. ''I
really want to take the bull by the horns, do my own thing,'' says
the 34-year-old comedian.
</P>
<P>
   Things are looking better for Dick, who has a small role in the
upcoming movie, ''Road Trip.'' He's also taping a pilot for NBC
written by ''American Pie'' writer Adam Herz, and he has several
films in the pipeline.
</P>
</TEXT>
