<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000429.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 12:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rep. Pelosi Eyes Leadership Post  </HEADLINE>
By BART JANSEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- If money equals power, Rep. Nancy Pelosi is
poised to exert serious clout.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, a seven-term Democrat from San Francisco, has given
$557,000 to other House candidates -- more than the combined total
of the rest of the House Democratic Caucus. And that has helped put
her in contention for a leadership position should Democrats win
back the House this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, who for years championed liberal causes in relative
anonymity, is campaigning to be majority whip, the third-ranking
job in the House. If she succeeds, she would be the highest-ranking
woman in congressional history.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nancy Pelosi's ascension to the leadership of the Democratic
Party will be a milestone both for women in America -- she will be
the first woman ever elected to the leadership -- and it will be an
enormous benefit to the state of California,'' said Rep. Tom
Lantos, D-Calif., who works with Pelosi on human rights issues.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi believes the key issues facing California, such as
immigration and regulating the Internet economy, are important for
the whole country. She said her experience working on them makes
her ready for a leadership position.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important to have somebody imbued with these issues,''
she said. ''It's not only about economic issues, it's about
education, environment, just about how we approach the challenges
of the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, 60, was born into a political family in Baltimore while
her father, Thomas D'Alesandro Jr., was in the midst of serving
five terms in the U.S. House. He later became mayor of Baltimore,
as did her brother, Thomas D'Alesandro III.
</P>
<P>
   ''Politics is the only life I ever knew,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Raynor, a Baltimore contemporary of Pelosi, joked she was
so young when she started stuffing campaign envelopes in the
basement of her family's home that it might have violated
child-labor laws.
</P>
<P>
   ''She learned politics at her father's knee,'' said Raynor, who
served 40 years as Maryland's state election administrator. ''They
were always very fine people and had their door open to anyone any
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi learned California's political ropes after marrying
businessman Paul Pelosi, with whom she has five children, and
moving West. She became chairwoman of the state Democratic Party,
which landed the 1984 national convention in San Francisco, and
then joined the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee for three
years.
</P>
<P>
   She won a special House election in 1987 after the incumbent
died, and has been entrenched in the liberal downtown San Francisco
district ever since, winning more than 80 percent of the votes in
her last three re-election campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi, who serves on the Appropriations Committee, enjoys top
rankings from groups supporting abortion rights, gun control, AIDS
research, unions and the environment. But she gets zero support
from abortion critics, business groups like Associated Builders and
Contractors, and the National Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   ABC criticized her for votes against bills limiting liability
for Y2K problems, reducing paperwork small businesses must file and
cutting taxes on capital gains and estates.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you look at Ms. Pelosi, she has not been a friend of
small business and reform,'' said Scott Brown, spokesman for ABC,
which represents 22,000 companies nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   While she generally has backed President Clinton's initiatives,
she sharply clashes with the administration on trade with China.
Pelosi is among the most outspoken critics of Clinton's call for
extending permanent most-favored nation trade status to China.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi says Clinton is ''either in denial or ill-informed''
about human rights abuses in China.
</P>
<P>
   While that position has put her at odds with some key
congressional Democrats, including California Sen. Dianne
Feinstein, who is otherwise an ally, Pelosi's fund-raising prowess
endears her to even more.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning of 1999 through early February, she had given
away $557,000, compared to $554,000 from the House Democratic
Caucus. She also raised $1.1 million for the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee, the fund-raising arm for House
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi tapped contributors almost entirely from San Francisco
and surrounding areas. She gave money to dozens of candidates but
said she targeted donations to those seeking to unseat Republicans
or in tight races.
</P>
<P>
   Should Democrats gain the six seats needed for a majority, those
who received money from Pelosi will be expected to support her for
whip, said Gary Jacobson, a political science professor at
University of California, San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   ''In politics, support is supposed to be reciprocated,'' he
said. ''It's a good strategy. It also shows that once you're
elected, you can protect them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi faces some stiff competition for the whip's job. Maryland
Rep. Steny Hoyer, who was caucus chairman when Democrats last held
the House, and Georgia Rep. John Lewis, the chief deputy minority
whip, are pursuing the job.
</P>
<P>
   Whips line up votes and shepherd legislation, an often
exhausting task. Supporters say Pelosi is well-suited to such a job
because she is among the hardest-working and most respected members
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nancy is a real straight shooter and she'll do the job for the
country,'' said Rep. Lynn Woolsey, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Pelosi's Web site: http://house.gov/pelosi
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
