<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Force Gen. Taking NATO Command  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS, AP Military Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gen. Joseph W. Ralston, who takes over as
supreme commander of NATO forces in Europe on Wednesday, has earned
great respect as both a warrior and diplomat in his 35-year Air
Force career. But unlike most of his predecessors in the NATO job,
he has little experience in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston, 56, will replace Army Gen. Wesley Clark as the top
commander of NATO forces. As is traditional, Ralston also will be
commander of U.S. European Command, in charge of all 100,000 U.S.
forces in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Officers who have worked with Ralston speak in glowing terms of
a man who entered the Air Force in 1965 through the Reserve Officer
Training Corps program at Miami University in Ohio, flew 147 combat
missions over Laos and North Vietnam and has been vice chairman of
the Joint Chiefs of Staff since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is absolutely the right person at the right time for this
job,'' Gen. James Jones, the commandant of the Marine Corps, said
in an interview Friday. Jones is a member of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff.
</P>
<P>
   ''If I were a European and I saw an officer the caliber of Joe
Ralston taking this job I would take it as a very strong sign that
the United States is serious about the importance of this
alliance,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston has held a wide variety of Air Force posts, including
commander of Alaskan Command at Elmendorf Air Force Base from 1992
to 1994 and commander of Air Combat Command at Langley Air Force
Base, Va., from 1995 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 Ralston was Defense Secretary William Cohen's first
choice to replace Gen. John Shalikashvili as chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, but Ralston withdrew his name after word got out
that he had had an affair 13 years in the past. At the time, the
Air Force was under heavy attack for having discharged a female
pilot, 1st Lt. Kelly Flinn, for lying about an illicit relationship
with a married man.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston, who was vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff
then, stayed on and was reappointed for a second term. The man who
became chairman instead of Ralston was Army Gen. Henry H. Shelton.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Friday, Shelton said Ralston's experience makes
him well suited for the NATO command.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one is more qualified than Joe Ralston to command the
military forces of this great alliance,'' Shelton said.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton and Cohen plan to fly to Mons, Belgium, home of NATO's
military command headquarters, to attend a public ceremony
Wednesday making Ralston the 13th supreme allied commander. A
similar ceremony will be held Tuesday in Stuttgart, Germany, for
Ralston's assuming command at U.S. European Command.
</P>
<P>
   In preparation for taking the job, Ralston consulted with
several former top NATO commanders, including retired Gen. George
Joulwan, who held the post for four years before Clark took over in
July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's very well suited for the job,'' Joulwan said in
an interview. He said there is little significance to the fact that
Ralston -- unlike most of his predecessors -- has never been
stationed in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ''More importantly, working for two chairmen (of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff) and two defense secretaries, he is very well aware
of the issues with regard to the alliance,'' Joulwan said. Ralston
also knows, through his years of contact with other NATO leaders,
that the commander job is demanding and sensitive.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have to be a statesman, a diplomat, you have to be
politically aware without being politically involved,'' Joulwan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston is only the second Air Force general to serve as supreme
NATO commander in Europe in the alliance's 51-year history. The
other was Gen. Lauris Norstad, who held the job from November 1956
to January 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Ralston, a native of Hopkinsville, Ky., had been prepared to
retire to Alaska this year when Cohen asked him to take the NATO
post. His term as vice chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff ended
Feb. 29, and by law he had to either assume another command within
60 days or end his career. Because of that constraint, Clark's
departure as supreme NATO commander was accelerated by a few months
to get Ralston into the job on time.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   NATO's home page at http://www.nato.int
</P>
<P>
   U.S. European Command at http://www.eucom.mil
</P>
