<HEADLINE> Key Dates in Lockerbie Bombing Case  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Key events in bombing of Pan Am Flight 103:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dec. 5, 1988 -- U.S. Embassy in Finland warned by telephone call
of plot to bomb Pan Am airliner on Frankfurt-U.S. flight. Several
other warnings of airline bombing received by U.S. missions in
December.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 21 -- Bomb destroys Pan Am Flight 103 over Lockerbie,
Scotland, killing all 259 on board and 11 on ground.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 30, 1989 -- German investigators say suitcase coming to
Frankfurt aboard Air Malta flight believed to have contained
Lockerbie bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 31 -- Swedish court document notes that two months before
bombing, a man tied to Syrian-based terror group visited Malta.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 30, 1991 -- French judge issues arrest warrant for Abdullah
Senoussi, brother-in-law of Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi, in
bombing of French jetliner over Africa in 1989 that killed 170.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 31 -- Washington Post reports French government has evidence
Lockerbie bombing planned by high-ranking Libyans, including
Senoussi.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 14 -- U.S. and Scottish authorities return indictments
against two alleged Libyan intelligence operatives, Abdel Basset
Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 28 -- Gadhafi refuses to hand men over.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 21, 1992 -- U.N. Security Council demands surrender of
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   April 15 -- Security Council imposes sanctions on air travel,
arms sales to Libya.
</P>
<P>
   March 18, 1993 -- Libya offers to turn suspects over to neutral
country for trial; U.S., Britain reject offer.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 11 -- Security Council adds sanctions freezing Libya's
foreign assets, banning its purchase of oil industry equipment.
</P>
<P>
   March 22, 1994 -- Libya offers to put suspects on trial before
Scottish judges at International Court of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   April 15 -- U.S. rejects offer.
</P>
<P>
   March 23, 1995 -- U.S. posts $4 million reward for capture of
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 3 -- President Clinton dedicates memorial to Lockerbie
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 5, 1996 -- Clinton orders sanctions against foreign
companies that invest in Libya.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 17 -- Al-Megrahi, Fhimah proclaim innocence on Libyan
television.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 21, 1997 -- Arab League urges member states to defy
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 23 -- South African President Nelson Mandela calls for
lifting of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 31 -- Pope John Paul II urges end to sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   April 15, 1998 -- Victims' families urge U.S., Britain to accept
trial in neutral country.
</P>
<P>
   June 10 -- Organization of African Unity announces it will no
longer abide by U.N. air embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Aug. 24 -- U.S., Britain accept trial in Netherlands under
Scottish law.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 18 -- Camp Zeist, former U.S. air base, chosen as trial
site.
</P>
<P>
   April 5, 1999 -- Libya extradites al-Megrahi and Fhimah to
Netherlands; U.N. suspends sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   June 7 -- Court delays trial to give defense more time.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 8 -- Defendants make first public appearance at Camp Zeist
pretrial hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Dec. 9 -- Judge rejects defense motion to throw out murder
conspiracy charge.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 2, 2000 -- Defense lawyers enter innocent pleas.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. 15 -- Scottish Chief Prosecutor Andrew Hardie resigns to
accept judgeship; replaced by Solicitor-General Colin Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   April 27 -- Judge rejects last-minute prosecution bid to delay
trial two months.
</P>
<P>
   May 3 -- Trial scheduled to begin; expected to last one year.
</P>
</TEXT>
