<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 13:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elian Fallout Affects Miami's Image  </HEADLINE>
By AMANDA RIDDLE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Armed federal agents raid a Little Havana home and
whisk away a 6-year-old Cuban boy. Baton-wielding riot police beat
demonstrators and arrest hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor criticizes the police chief and fires the city
manager. The police chief quits, saying he's tired of the mayor's
destructive politics.
</P>
<P>
   It's no wonder Miami comes across as a chaotic, polarized city
that Florida Gov. Jeb Bush said ''can't control itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Images broadcast worldwide a week ago showed Miami in turmoil:
Protesters torched piles of tires and toppled park benches into the
street to vent their anger over federal agents' seizure of young
Elian Gonzalez from his Miami relatives' home; police fired tear
gas into the crowds and arrested more than 300 people.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Joe Carollo demanded the police chief's firing for failing
to inform him about the raid. City Manager Donald Warshaw refused,
and Carollo fired him.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo insisted Warshaw's firing had nothing to do with the
Elian case. He said Warshaw has been criticizing him, lying and
trying to turn department heads against him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Politically, it makes Miami the laughingstock of the United
States,'' said Jim Corey, a University of Miami political science
professor. ''It will be a long time for healing, if it ever
occurs.''
</P>
<P>
   Author and Miami Herald columnist Carl Hiassen, in a recent
column in The New York Times, described Miami as a place where
''fact is routinely more fantastic than fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   The city of 375,000 has been beset for years by periodic
episodes of crime, political corruption and economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1980s it was a scene of drug deals and killings
committed by ''cocaine cowboys.'' In the early 1990s, six tourists
were slain in the Miami area.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo became mayor after his predecessor, Xavier Suarez, was
unseated over a vote fraud scandal in 1997. A year earlier, a
former city manager was sentenced to prison in a corruption
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The same year, the state appointed a fiscal oversight board -- a
first in Florida -- after the city discovered a $68 million budget
shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   Then, last Thanksgiving, Elian was found clinging to an inner
tube at sea after a boat carrying his mother and other would-be
refugees sank in attempt to sail from Cuba to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Elian became the center of an international custody fight
between his Cuban father who wanted him returned to Cuba and his
Miami relatives who said he deserved U.S. citizenship. Scores of
members of Miami's anti-Castro Cuban exile community gathered
around the house where Elian was staying in the city's Little
Havana section, demanding the boy not be sent back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The attention and political wrangling over the case further
fractured Miami's ethnic community.
</P>
<P>
   Haitian residents criticized local leaders for failing to rally
behind their causes as they had the Cubans'. Some people outside
the Cuban-American community were appalled at Elian's Miami
relatives' defiance of Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ''The picture that is being painted is an unstable Miami, a
Miami that can't control itself, a Miami that can't govern
itself,'' Bush said last week on a visit to the city, where he has
a home.
</P>
<P>
   Carollo has decried the criticism and comparisons of Miami city
government to third-world countries. He said the nation would
quickly forget the city's latest public relations nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Blumberg, chairman-elect of the Greater Miami Chamber of
Commerce, said people outside Miami need to understand that only a
small portion of the 800,000 Cuban-Americans in the Miami area are
protesting.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not what Miami is about,'' he said. ''It's what an
impassioned group of people feels on a weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Adams, a journalism and public relations professor at
Florida International University in Miami, said the disruptions
surrounding Elian shouldn't harm tourism, the city's second-largest
industry. He noted that visitors continued coming even after 18
people died during a 1980 race riot that erupted when five white
police officers were acquitted in the beating death of a young
black man.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we were suddenly to lose the sun and the warmth and the
water,'' Adams said, ''then we'd worry.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 1309 </TRAILER>
