<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 13:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Benetton, Toscani End Partnership  </HEADLINE>
By CANDICE HUGHES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Benetton and the photographer who used everything
from AIDS victims to U.S. death row inmates in his shocking ads for
the company have split after an 18-year creative partnership, a
statement announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Benetton thanked Oliviero Toscani in the statement for his
''fundamental contribution to the 'new' advertising.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Luckily, nothing is forever,'' Toscani said in the statement.
''It's good to have the courage to end something that was
fantastic, and still have the enthusiasm to take on new projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Toscani's in-your-face campaigns for Benetton's clothes have
been both damned and praised. Some defend them as fearless social
activism, while others say they are nothing more than crass
exploitation.
</P>
<P>
   To sell trendy clothes, the ads used a host of unconventional
subjects -- including smooching nuns and priests, mating horses, a
bloodied soldier's uniform, newborn babies, AIDS victims and
condemned murderers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no such thing as going too far,'' Toscani once said.
</P>
<P>
   His partnership with Luciano Benetton, who gave Toscani a very
free rein, was legendary. Toscani once compared his patron to a
Renaissance pope and himself to Michelangelo.
</P>
<P>
   The statement gave no reason for the breakup, and neither
Toscani nor company officials were available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   But Toscani's wife, Kristi, said by telephone that ''after so
many years the decision was mutual.'' She also said it had nothing
to do with the death penalty campaign, which cost Benetton an
important U.S. contract.
</P>
<P>
   Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. dumped Benetton's line from its stores in
February after an outcry from victims rights groups and threats of
a boycott.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign also created legal problems. The state of Missouri
is suing Benetton, claiming the state was deceived by the law
professor who arranged the death row visits. The suit claims the
project's commercial purpose was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Toscani, the ''bad boy of advertising,'' is also the creative
director of Tina Brown's Talk magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Benetton said its advertising would be turned over to Fabrica, a
cutting-edge multimedia research group in Treviso. Fabrica was
founded in 1993 by Toscani and bankrolled by Benetton.
</P>
<P>
   Under Toscani's guidance, Fabrica produced the Benetton magazine
Colors, and increasingly did projects for outside clients as well.
</P>
<P>
   Fabrica is as provocative as its founder. One issue of Colors on
AIDS included a computer-generated image of former President Ronald
Reagan with the skin blemishes associated with the disease. An
issue on motherhood featured several pages of close-up photos of
female genitals.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Benetton (with links to Fabrica, Colors):
http://www.benetton.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 1310 </TRAILER>
