<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 13:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sunday's gay rights march causing rift in New York  </HEADLINE>
By GARY CRAIG, 
Rochester Democrat and Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- A major gay and lesbian march planned for
Sunday in Washington, D.C., has caused a schism among activists,
many of whom are refusing to attend.
</P>
<P>
   While not urging a boycott, New York's Empire State Pride
Agenda, a gay and lesbian lobbying organization with 25,000
members, has not endorsed the ''Millennium March on Washington for
Equality.''
</P>
<P>
   Major groups nationwide that lobby for gay and lesbian rights
are not backing the march, either.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers expect 300,000 people at the fourth rally for gay,
lesbian and bisexual people in Washington in the past 21 years. The
march has been planned for years to mobilize supporters into a
voting bloc this presidential election year.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, the rift is because of disagreements with the national
organizations that have planned the march, including the Human
Rights Campaign. But some gay activists say there's another reason
many won't attend: It will be a waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel that the timing of the march is ill-advised at best,''
said Matt Foreman, Pride Agenda's executive director. ''It's a
lame-duck Congress, a lame-duck president.''
</P>
<P>
   As well, Foreman said, most of the legislative battles for gay
rights are waged at the state, not national, level, and many state
legislatures are now in session. That's where political pressure
needs most to be exerted, not in the nation's capital, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just saying it's not a good use of our community's
scarce resources,'' he said of the march.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Richards, the western New York field organizer for the
Pride Agenda, said activists here are marshaling their energy to
push for a New York ''hate crimes'' bill, which increases criminal
penalties for bias-related crimes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel spending time locally is more productive,'' said
Richards, who works out of Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   Rochester resident Sabrina Kinckle is traveling to the march.
She said she thinks the event can energize people like herself, who
then can return to fight for changes at the local and state levels.
</P>
<P>
   ''I understand that there are a lot of politics behind going to
the march,'' she said. ''But some people still find it necessary to
go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
