<HEADLINE> Missiles Untouched in India Fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- A massive blaze ripped through a
military armory, killing three civilians and blowing up nearly
10,000 tons of ammunition, but leaving missile stockpiles
untouched, news reports said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At least 12 people were injured by flying metal during the blaze
at the armory of the Bharatpur Ordnance Depot in northern India,
which set off deafening explosions throughout the day Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities ordered thousands of residents of Bharatpur to leave
the town immediately, fearing damage by shrapnel.
</P>
<P>
   After battling the blaze for 20 hours, fire fighters brought it
under control Saturday, Press Trust of India news agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The dump stores heavy caliber shells of 130mm long-range guns
and other explosives. Press Trust of India said surface-to-air and
anti-tank missiles also at the site were not damaged in the fire.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister George Fernandes met Saturday with military
commanders in New Delhi about the fire, then visited Bharatpur, 110
miles south of New Delhi, to inspect the dump.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandes told reporters that a preliminary investigation
suggested that the dry elephant grass in the complex caught fire,
leading to explosions, but he said the full facts were not yet
known.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
