<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Europe Exchange Merger Set  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- A planned fusion of the Frankfurt and
London stock exchanges, which would create the largest such
operation in Europe, appears to be set, a major newspaper said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung, citing sources negotiating
the plan, said the German side planned to announce its merger plans
Wednesday, with the merger's completion expected by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   The London Stock Exchange announced last week it was in merger
talks with Deutsche Bourse. Such a merger would unite the
continent's two largest stock markets and lead to volume that could
make stock trading cheaper, the London exchange said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the newspaper, the supervisory board of Frankfurt's
Deutsche Bourse AG has now decided in favor of a fusion. The
supervisory board of the London exchange is to discuss the plan
further on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides would have a 50 percent share in the partnership,
which is to be headquartered in London, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   The joint trading system would be the so-called Xetra, retaining
the current indicators, such as the DAX.
</P>
<P>
   Werner Seifert, the current board chairman of the Deutsche
Bourse AG, would probably be named to head the merged operations,
the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a three-way regional exchange was formed by stock
markets in Paris, Brussels and Amsterdam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
