<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barely bearable day for bruins awakening from hibernation  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Bears in northern New Jersey were a bit late
awakening from
their winter slumber this year, but some motorists and residents
likely wish the huge creatures had slept even longer.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Friday alone, three bears were struck by vehicles on North
Jersey highways, two of them fatally, while another who got stuck
up the tree kept wildlife officials on the run for hours, and a
fifth bear somehow fell into an open septic tank.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's spring, and they're coming out of their dens late, so
things are starting to happen,'' said Sharon Southard, spokeswoman
for the state Department of Environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife officials on Saturday received reports of bears getting
into garbage and bird feeders.
</P>
<P>
   One of the bears killed Friday was a 150-pound young male
crossing Route 80 in Mount Olive, police said.
</P>
<P>
   In Vernon, a 350-pound male that apparently suffered two broken
legs after being struck on Route 515 was put down by police.
</P>
<P>
   Another large bear that was struck in Byram survived his
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ''He just shook his head and said, 'You'll have to do better
than that,' and walked away,'' Bob Erikson, a biologist with the
state Division of Fish and Wildlife, told The Star-Ledger of Newark
in Saturday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   In Butler, a male climbed a giant tulip tree and stayed for
seven hours until he was shot with a tranquilizer and lowered in a
fire truck bucket.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife officials who tranquilized the bear said it was likely
chased off its territory by larger males.
</P>
<P>
   ''Big males chase smaller males out of their territory around
this time of year,'' Ken Kroeze, a division officer, told The
Record of Hackensack in Saturday's editions. ''That's probably what
happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   Erikson predicted residents in the northern half of the state
could expect many more bear encounters until hot summer weather
slows the animals down.
</P>
<P>
   Last year in New Jersey, 62 bears were struck and 46 were killed
by motorists.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints that the larger and more brazen black bear population
in northern New Jersey have invaded back yards, killed pets and
scared small children prompted the state Fish and Game Council to
propose New Jersey's first bear hunt since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The bear population, which numbered fewer than 100 two decades
ago, has reached an all-time high of more than 1,000 in 11 of the
state's 21 counties, according to the council. Damage complaints
soared from 285 in 1995 to 1,659 in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-29-00 1451 </TRAILER>
