<DOCNO> APW20000429.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Releases AP Photographer  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- A photographer for The Associated Press
was released from a cold and dirty jail cell Saturday after
spending three nights behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   But police confiscated Obed Zilwa's passport and plane ticket
and ordered him to report to authorities Tuesday morning. At that
time, Zimbabwe's attorney general will issue a document saying the
government has no interest in prosecuting him, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Security forces arrested Zilwa, a highly regarded South African
photojournalist, on Wednesday and accused him of the April 22
bombing of The Daily News, Zimbabwe's only independent daily
newspaper. Zilwa, who had photographed the damage caused by the
blast, repeatedly said he was innocent. International press
organizations demanded his immediate release.
</P>
<P>
   His arrest was widely seen as an attempt to intimidate the
foreign press, which has been covering political turmoil and
violent occupations of white-owned farms in this southeast African
country.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole thing was politically related,'' Zilwa said. ''There
were police officers who called me 'journalist bomber,' but after
that I was treated quite well.''
</P>
<P>
   Just before his release, Zilwa was reunited for the first time
since his ordeal began with his pregnant wife, Leonora de
Sousa-Zilwa. Accompanied by a South African diplomat, Zilwa's
attorney and an AP reporter, the couple then got into the
diplomat's Land Rover and were dropped off at their hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Zilwa told colleagues that police informed him Friday they had
no case against him and sought higher authority to free him. The
duty officer in the attorney general's office ordered the police to
release Zilwa into his lawyer's custody.
</P>
<P>
   Zilwa, who is based in Cape Town, said he was not mistreated
though he described uncomfortable conditions in the jail cell at
Harare's central police station.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was not pushed around,'' Zilwa said. But he added that he
had been worried about his fate, especially after a 48-hour
deadline for him to have been charged or released passed with no
action taken.
</P>
<P>
   He described hygiene standards in police cells as ''not up to
standard.'' His shoes had been removed and he suffered from the
cold until colleagues sent in warm clothing and blankets.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after the bombing, police said they were
suspicious that foreign journalists arrived at the scene so
quickly. Many of the journalists were staying at the nearby Meikles
Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Zilwa said he was driving back to his hotel on April 22 after
socializing with friends when he heard an explosion and stopped to
question two policemen on duty near government buildings two blocks
from the newspaper's offices in downtown Harare.
</P>
<P>
   ''As I journalist, I stopped to ask police in the area. I went
back to the hotel to get my gear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said eyewitness accounts implicating Zilwa had either
been disproved or were untraceable.
</P>
<P>
   Zilwa's attorney, Jonathan Samkange, said police had
acknowledged the photographer's continued detention was illegal
under the 48-hour limit for charging or release.
</P>
<P>
   Zilwa was arrested as he waited in the Harare airport for his
flight back to South Africa. He has been covering the political
violence in Zimbabwe for the past month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 1455 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000429.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
