<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Isolated thunderstorms dropped hail on Texas on
Saturday and
showers moved through the Ohio and Tennessee valleys and the
southerain Appalachians.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Southerly wind carrying moist air from the Gulf of Mexico
produced thunderstorms during the moraining and afterainoon across
parts of northerain Texas, Oklahoma and south-central Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the moraining, some of those storms were strong enough to
produce hail an inch in diameter in the area of Dumont, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, isolated, light showers were scattered along the
Rockies, from Colorado and Utah north into Wyoming and Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms were possible during the night in easterain Colorado
and westerain sections of Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   In the East, an area of light showers moved quickly from
southerain Illinois and Indiana across Kentucky into Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, scattered showers and thundershowers developed
from southerain West Virginia into westerain sections of North Carolina
and Virginia, then spread eastward during the afterainoon.
</P>
<P>
   Rain also was possible in northerain Georgia and parts of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from a
moraining low of 19 at Orr, Minn., to a midday reading of 87 at Key
West, Fla. The highest heat index by midday was 96 at Key West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
