<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Urges Synchronized Primaries  </HEADLINE>
By EUN-KYUNG KIM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hoping to prevent a repeat of this year's rush
by states to be among the first to hold presidential primaries, a
Democratic panel approved a report Saturday that urged the
Republican party to adopt the same nominating calendar as
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee allows states to hold their
primaries and caucuses as early as the first Tuesday in March and
as late as the second Tuesday in June. Only Iowa and New Hampshire
may hold their elections outside that window.
</P>
<P>
   But the Republican National Committee sets no such limits,
causing states to leapfrog each other and crowd the GOP calendar
with many primaries and caucuses as early as February.
</P>
<P>
   The ''front-loading'' problem has forced Democratic officials in
many states to unsuccessfully seek permission to hold their
primaries earlier to save money and stay competitive with state
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A report approved unanimously by the Democratic Party's rules
committee urges the Republican party to adopt a window similar to
the one used by Democrats. It also encourages Democratic officials
to ''urge the Republican Party to establish sanctions to enforce
its window and discourage states from going before the window in an
attempt to leapfrog other states.''
</P>
<P>
   The report will be sent to the party's national chairman, Joe
Andrew. While Democratic rules don't require action on 2004 prior
to this election, Democrats agreed to work closely with Republicans
to examine potential changes.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Purpuro, a spokesman for the RNC, said he couldn't address
specifics of the Democratic report but said that both parties
''have made every effort to at least keep each other informed of
their respective efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a Republican advisory panel also has been examining ways
to curb the front-loading problem. The committee will present its
own report during a news conference Tuesday in Washington. Those
recommendations will then be considered by the party's rules
committee next month in Indianapolis. Any changes would be made by
the full RNC at the national convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Various primary plans have been considered by both parties over
the last year, but Democrats decided to leave what it considered a
good system untouched.
</P>
<P>
   ''Criticism about a front-loaded schedule has to be weighed
against a process that seems to be working well,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other options that have been suggested by both parties: a
regional primary plan that would divide the country into four areas
and rotate which one could hold primaries first.
</P>
<P>
   Another plan would be based on size and allow smaller states,
somewhat larger states, midsize states and finally the largest
states to hold primaries in groups of 10 to 12 on one-a-month
primary days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 1515 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
