<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 15:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Receives Soviet-Seized Art  </HEADLINE>
By KRISTINA SHEVORY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia (AP) -- In an emotional ceremony, German
officials Saturday returned two pieces of looted art to a czarist
palace outside St. Petersburg, more than half a century after they
were seized by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the intricately inlaid chest and glistening
mosaic from Peter the Great's famed Amber Room, Russia has agreed
to turn over 101 artworks looted from Germany by Soviet troops
after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first such swap of so-called ''trophy art'' taken by
their countries' armies during and after the war. But it marked
only a single step in settling a debate that has weighed on
otherwise warming relations between Russia and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ''People in Russia understand, value and treasure Russian-German
relations,'' a somber Russian President Vladimir Putin said in his
address at the ornate Yekaterinsky Palace.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even the most difficult questions, including exchanges of
cultural valuables, can be solved if they are approached calmly and
constructively.''
</P>
<P>
   German Culture Minister Michael Naumann called it a ''symbolic
event'' and said he hoped it would be the first of many such swaps.
</P>
<P>
   But talks have not resolved ownership disputes for most of more
than one million cultural valuables Germany claims Soviets troops
took -- paintings, rare books, coins and other items such as church
windows.
</P>
<P>
   A Russian law largely bans repatriating booty art, seen by
Russians as just compensation for an estimated several hundred
thousand items destroyed or lost during the Nazi occupation.
Complicating ownership claims, some of the items were looted twice,
first by the Nazis from occupied countries and then by the Soviets.
</P>
<P>
   For Russians, the Amber Room is the most sensitive symbol of the
trophy art debate. The room was a gift to Russia's Peter the Great
from Frederick William I of Prussia in 1716. Its walls were plated
in 1,300 square feet of resplendent amber mosaics, placed near
mirrors and windows to glow a rich golden-brown color.
</P>
<P>
   Invading Nazi troops hastily stripped the chamber in 1941 and
shipped it west. It disappeared in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Only fragments have been found. The room is being restored with
financing from Germany's Ruhrgas.
</P>
<P>
   The mosaic handed over Saturday is called ''Sense of Smell and
Touch'' and depicts a scene of women frolicking by a pool. The
mosaic and chest were discovered in private collections in Germany
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Naumann received a license to return a total of 101
drawings and watercolors by Henri Toulouse-Lautrec, Francisco Goya
and dozens of German artists to a museum in Bremen.
</P>
<P>
   The German Embassy in Moscow has held the works since a Russian
World War II veteran anonymously turned over the art in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Long only rumored to exist, the Soviet Union's vast cache of
stolen masterpieces was confirmed by Russia only in the early
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most controversial items is the Trojan gold excavated
in Turkey in 1873 by German archaeologist Heinrich Schliemann, who
believed that it once belonged to the king of the ancient city of
Troy. The items are on display at Moscow's Pushkin museum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
