<HEADLINE> Sources: WPP Group Talks Break Off  </HEADLINE>
By SKIP WOLLENBERG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- For a second time this year, talks have broken
down in WPP Group PLC's attempts to acquire Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc.
and become the world's biggest advertising and marketing company,
two sources close to the discussions said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But New York-based Y&AMP;R, whose clients include AT&AMP;T, Ford Motor
Co., Colgate-Palmolive and Citibank, was continuing discussions
about a combination with another European ad company, Publicis SA
of France, according to one of the sources.
</P>
<P>
   Both sources spoke on condition that they not be identified.
Calls to the companies for comment were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising industry has been consolidating in recent years
as agencies seek the global reach and versatile marketing skills
demanded by the multinational companies who are their biggest
clients.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear exactly what led to the breakdown in talks
between Y&AMP;R and WPP Group, the British parent of the New York-based
ad agencies J. Walter Thompson and Ogilvy &AMP; Mather. Their talks
began several months ago and broke down in mid-March before
resuming again about 10 days ago, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The talks broke down last night and the negotiations have been
terminated,'' one of the sources said Saturday. He said there was
disagreement over provisions related to severance and autonomy but
declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The other source said there was no price agreement as well as
''serious contractual issues'' involving Y&AMP;R employees and
disagreement over how much autonomy Y&AMP;R would be allowed in serving
its clients.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R is a 77-year-old ad company that went public for the first
time about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   WPP was a onetime wire-basket maker that was transformed into an
advertising powerhouse under its leader Martin Sorrell with the
hostile acquisitions of the venerable J. Walter Thompson and Ogilvy
&AMP; Mather agencies in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   According to one source, WPP had offered stock worth about $65 a
share for Y&AMP;R in March, which would have valued Y&AMP;R at about $5.46
billion. Y&AMP;R shares rose $2.81\ to $55.68\ on Friday in trading on
the New York Stock Exchange after a $3 a share rise on Thursday
when WPP confirmed it was in talks with Y&AMP;R.
</P>
<P>
   WPP is the third-biggest ad organization in the world based on
1999 revenue of about $4.82 billion, according to the trade
publication Advertising Age.
</P>
<P>
   Y&AMP;R ranked seventh on that list with about $1.87 billion in
revenue while Publicis was 10th at $1.43 billion.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of WPP and Y&AMP;R would have allowed WPP to vault
past the two bigger ad companies on the Ad Age list -- Omnicom Group
at $5.74 billion in revenue and Interpublic Group of Companies at
$5.08 billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   A Y&AMP;R merger with Publicis would rank fourth behind WPP.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
