<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish City Readies for Arson Trial  </HEADLINE>
By KIM GAMEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOTEBORG, Sweden (AP) -- Leo Papini felt pleased as his
16-year-old daughter went off to a dance. She had agreed to go on a
family excursion, and in exchange, he decided to let her stay out
late.
</P>
<P>
   He was to pick her up at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   But when Papini arrived at the dance hall in the southwestern
port city of Goteborg on Oct. 29, 1998, a horrific scene awaited
him: flames were shooting out of the building's broken windows and
acrid smoke filled the air.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to push past firefighters to reach his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ''But it was too late,'' he said recently. Moa was one of 63
youths who died when fire raced through the second-floor disco that
was jammed beyond capacity. More than 200 people were injured, 50
seriously, in the worst fire in Swedish history. On Wednesday, four
people are to stand trial in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the youths attending the dance were immigrants or
children of immigrants -- like Moa, whose father came from Italy in
the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was becoming a real young lady,'' the 65-year-old
architect said, holding back tears.
</P>
<P>
   Shoresh Kaveh, 19, Housein Arsani, 19, Mohammad Mohammadamini,
21, and Meysam Mohammadyeh, 19, all born in Iran but now living in
Sweden, are charged with aggravated arson and face trial in
Goteborg, 300 miles southwest of Stockholm.
</P>
<P>
   The four men denied the allegations. But defense attorneys
acknowledged at least three of the defendants were present at the
stairwell where the fire started.
</P>
<P>
   The four were arrested earlier this year but only formally
charged last week after investigators eliminated other leads
yielded by 1,800 interviews and an award of up to $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities suspected arson from the beginning because the fire
spread so fast. Fifteen investigators and two prosecutors worked
exclusively on the case.
</P>
<P>
   A conviction on an aggravated arson charge can carry a sentence
of six years to life in prison, but Swedish law would allow a
lesser sentence because the suspects were under age 20 at the time
of the fire.
</P>
<P>
   The court proceedings had to be moved to an exhibition center
that will be divided into three rooms to accommodate 500 relatives
of the victims and survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said flammable liquid was poured over chairs stacked
in the emergency stairwell and set on fire after an argument broke
out with the party's organizers over the entrance fee.
</P>
<P>
   The dance was organized by four teen-agers who rented a room at
the cultural Macedonian Association during a holiday week. About
400 people were crammed into a space legally licensed for 150 when
the fire broke out.
</P>
<P>
   The fire spread so quickly that people had little time to escape
the searing flames and smoke. Panicked teen-agers were forced to
flee down a single, narrow staircase. Many people leapt from
second-story windows.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have been thinking about this tragedy when we leave the
police (station), at home and on weekends,'' chief prosecutor Ulf
Noren said recently. ''We know that if we find the cause, the
survivors and relatives can finally know what happened and get on
with their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Papini, who is chairman of an association of victims' relatives
and survivors, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''A victim wants the truth and wants satisfaction,'' said
Papini. ''Then you can go home and say now justice was done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 1606 </TRAILER>
