<HEADLINE> Blast at Hamburg Disco Injures 9  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMBURG, Germany (AP) -- A grenade hidden in a crowded Hamburg
discotheque went off early Saturday morning, sending nine people to
the hospital, two of them in critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   When the grenade exploded shortly after 3 a.m., about 1,500
people were at the disco, located in a renovated wartime air raid
shelter in Germany's second-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   Police said earlier that eight people were hurt in the blast,
but revised the number to nine after a man contacted them and said
he had left the club on his own after the explosion to seek
treatment for back injuries from his regular doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Six men and two women -- between the ages of 18 and 32 -- suffered
injuries to their arms, legs and bodies. One person was hit in the
eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The motive for the attack was not clear, and police had no leads
on suspects, police spokesman Hans-Juergen Petersen said.
</P>
<P>
   The fragmentation hand grenade that police said was
Yugoslav-built had been hidden in a room separated from the club's
dance floor when it detonated.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the explosive device was hidden between some seats,
but were not sure how it was set off.
</P>
</TEXT>
