<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: 36 Journalists Killed in '99  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- The number of journalists killed in 1999 nearly
doubled to 36 from the year before, though slightly fewer reporters
were put behind bars, according to a Paris-based media advocacy
group.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters Without Borders' annual report, released this week,
shows that the struggle for press freedom around the world remains
an upward climb, with the Internet the latest target of
authoritarian governments.
</P>
<P>
   Press freedom does not exist in more than 20 nations that are
home to about 2 billion people, and ''truly (can) be said to
exist'' only in about 30 countries where less than 1 billion live,
the report said. Press freedom is ''random and unreliable''
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, there were 85 journalists in prison, ''slightly
fewer'' than in 1998 when there were 93.
</P>
<P>
   However, 36 journalists were killed worldwide, nearly double the
1998 toll of 19.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 446 were reported arrested, and 653 attacked and
threatened, the report said. Another 69 journalists disappeared in
1999. And about 400 media outfits were victims of bans,
suspensions, seizures or censorship.
</P>
<P>
   In March, another media advocacy group, International Press
Institute, reported that 87 journalists and media staff were killed
while working in 1999. Reporters Without Borders said it counted
only reporters among the 36 deaths and did not take into account
staff, such as drivers or interpreters.
</P>
<P>
   The number of journalists killed had been dropping until 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In Sierra Leone, at least nine journalists were killed last
year, including Myles Tierney of Associated Press Television News.
More journalists were killed in sub-Saharan Africa in 1999 than in
the four previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Asia -- where six journalists were killed in 1999 and eight
others died in suspicious circumstances -- is the continent with the
most journalists in jail. Burma is the ''world's biggest prison for
the press,'' keeping 13 journalists behind bars, the group said.
The group's ''worst offenders'' in jailing journalists also
included Syria, with 10 jailings, and China and Ethiopia, each with
nine.
</P>
<P>
   In Cuba, four journalists have been arrested, and six put under
house arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Violence waned slightly in the Americas, where six journalists
were murdered, compared to eight in 1998. All six killed in 1999
were in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia was the European focal point for journalistic
hardship in 1999, with six journalists killed, three foreign
correspondents held by the Yugoslav military under suspicion of
spying and more than 80 thrown out during the NATO bombing
campaign. Three of the journalists killed were from the official
Chinese media, their Belgrade Embassy hit by NATO bombs.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has become the latest target of authoritarian
governments. The organization said at least 20 countries could be
described as ''enemies of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Reporters without Borders:
http://www.press-freedom.org/indexuk.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 1616 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000429.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
