<HEADLINE> Ex-Guerrilla Agrees To Aid Victims  </HEADLINE>
By JAMAL HALABY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- A former Palestinian guerrilla who claims
he ordered the burial of three Israeli soldiers during the 1982
invasion of Lebanon said Saturday he was willing to help locate
their remains.
</P>
<P>
   Ghazi Atalla said, however, that he has little other information
that could be of use to the families of Israeli servicemen still
missing in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has put a high priority on finding its only MIAs in
Lebanon: Zachary Baumel, Zvi Feldman, Yehuda Katz, and air force
navigator Ron Arad. Some reports say they were captured and taken
to Damascus, while others say they were killed and buried in Syria
or Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am willing to give information and even if the families call
me or come to me I will give them what they need,'' Atalla told The
Associated Press in an interview at his Amman residence.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Arabic language newspaper Kol el Arab recently quoted
Atalla as saying that he had overseen the burial of three soldiers'
bodies after a battle in Lebanon and that he had offered to reveal
the location of the graves in exchange for Palestinian prisoners
held in Israeli jails. Israel's Hebrew-language daily Maariv
reported that Atalla had personally buried the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Atalla told the AP that the Arabic language newspaper had
''completely misquoted me and put words in my mouth,''
</P>
<P>
   Atalla said that in the early days of the June 6, 1982 invasion,
Israeli troops destroyed Syrian tanks and missiles and advanced to
the positions of Palestinian guerillas, known as Fidayeen,
scattering them.
</P>
<P>
   ''During heavy fighting, one of my soldiers said there were
bodies of three Israeli soldiers on the battlefield,'' Atalla said.
''I told him 'bury them.'''
</P>
<P>
   ''I did not see the bodies, or know the exact burial location
and I don't recall the Palestinian soldier who had buried them,''
said Atalla then a colonel in charge of some 4,000 Palestinian
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Atalla said he did not know the dead soldiers' names or ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Israel says the three soldiers went missing after a June 11,
1982 battle in southern Lebanon, about 5 miles west of the Syrian
border.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes for obtaining information about Israeli MIA's who went
missing in Lebanon have faded amid pessimism over the chances of
resuming peace talks between Israel and Syria, the main power
broker in Lebanon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
