<HEADLINE> New Japan, Russia Leaders Meet  </HEADLINE>
By GENNADY KONOPLYOV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia (AP) -- Addressing each other informally
as ''Yoshi'' and ''Volodya,'' the new leaders of Japan and Russia
met Saturday and seemed to achieve their immediate goal --
establishing a friendly personal relationship -- but avoided all
thorny issues.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori arrived in St. Petersburg on Friday
night on his first foreign trip as Japan's leader. He and Russian
President Vladimir Putin, who was elected last month, held private
talks in the Russian Museum and the Hermitage on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The discussion covered economic ties and preparations for this
summer's summit in Okinawa of the Group of Eight -- the world's top
seven industrialized democracies plus Russia, Putin and Mori told
journalists after the talks.
</P>
<P>
   A smiling Mori also announced that the two had decided to
address each other as ''Yoshi'' and ''Volodya.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we have begun forming a good personal relationship,''
Putin said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin also thanked Mori for making Russia the site of his first
foreign trip, saying: ''This is a very good sign for our
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   But the leaders avoided the main problem in Russian-Japanese
relations -- the bitter dispute over who owns the Kuril Islands.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides claim four small islands in the South Kuril chain
that Soviet troops seized after World War II. The dispute has
prevented the countries from signing a formal peace treaty to end
the war.
</P>
<P>
   ''During these talks, we confirmed intentions of signing the
peace agreement,'' Mori said. But the Kuril issue itself was not
mentioned, according to Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov, who
attended the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Mori said he hoped his friendly relationship with Putin would
serve as a foundation for tackling the more difficult issues later.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like for the president and me to use the opportunities
of our friendship for further dialogue,'' Mori said.
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese government official said the two leaders agreed to
try to sign the peace treaty by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Mori's trip was arranged when he was still second-in-command in
Japan's governing party; he became prime minister this month after
Keizo Obuchi became incapacitated by a stroke.
</P>
<P>
   ''When my predecessor was seriously ill, he asked me to continue
Russian-Japanese relations,'' Mori said Saturday. ''And these words
I took as guidance in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Mori and Russian officials have said that one of the key
purposes of Saturday's summit would be the establishment of a
personal relationship between the new leaders of Japan and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's spokesman Alexei Gromov said later Saturday that Putin
would travel to Japan in late August, Russian news agencies
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Putin and Mori also exchanged diplomatic notes on an investment
protection agreement, which is to take effect in a month.
</P>
<P>
   Mori planned to leave Sunday for Western Europe to hold talks
with his Italian, French, German and British counterparts, before
heading to Canada. The premier's nine-day trip is to conclude with
talks with President Clinton on May 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
