<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling Party Nominates Ghana's VP  </HEADLINE>
By KWASI KPODO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACCRA, Ghana (AP) -- Ghana's ruling party on Saturday endorsed
Vice President John Evans Atta Mills as its presidential candidate
for December elections.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination by the National Democratic Congress foreshadows
the end of the era of President Jerry Rawlings, who has dominated
Ghanaian politics since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Mills was the only candidate for the nomination, but a crowd of
supporters still roared in appreciation when it was announced he
had been given the nod during a party meeting held in Ho, about 110
miles north of Accra.
</P>
<P>
   Mills, a former law professor, said he would guarantee a nation
of equal opportunity for every Ghanaian in education, health care
and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I shall form a new government with a team of experienced and
skillful people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He praised Rawlings, who saw the nation through years of
military rule before it emerged as one of Africa's most democratic
nations.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlings ruled during two repressive military juntas beginning
in 1979, but eventually oversaw a transition to civilian rule that
has made Ghana a bulwark of stability in troubled West Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
