<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush optimistic about McCain meeting  </HEADLINE>
By BETH GARDINER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Texas Gov. George Bush said Saturday he hopes to
find common ground with defeated presidential rival John McCain in
a meeting McCain almost canceled because of disagreements over the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ''I look forward to discussing a wide range of issues with
John'' at the planned May 9 talk, Bush said during a brief visit to
a gathering of radio talk show hosts in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to remind him -- he knows this, I know it -- that
there's a lot we agree on, like Social Security reform,
governmental reform, education reform,'' Bush said. ''And I'm going
to talk to him about the general election, hopefully he'll campaign
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush would like to gain the support of his defeated but still
popular primary opponent, who has not endorsed the presumptive
Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's supporting me, and I appreciate that,'' Bush said. ''He's
a straightforward person. When he says he wants me to be the
president, I'm confident he does want me to be the president.''
</P>
<P>
   But relations between the men's camps have been strained since
McCain suspended his campaign last month.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and his advisers were irritated by Bush's announcement
that he would ask the Arizona senator in their first face-to-face
meeting since the primaries whether he was willing to serve as vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said repeatedly that he doesn't want the job, and
told aides to cancel the meeting unless they could be assured that
Bush wanted to hold substantial talks on a variety of topics.
</P>
<P>
   An agenda agreed upon by the two campaigns on Friday was said to
include McCain's signature issue of campaign finance overhaul along
with military reform, Social Security, education, health care,
making the GOP more inclusive and McCain's role in the fall
campaign and the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, to be held in Pittsburgh, will be important to the
political fortunes of both Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wants to unify the party and appeal to the
independent-minded voters galvanized by McCain's campaign. McCain,
who still has presidential ambitions, wants to show Republicans he
is a party man.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments came in an interview with WOR-AM radio, shortly
after the Texas governor spoke at the National Association of Radio
Talk Show Hosts convention on Manhattan's Upper West Side.
</P>
<P>
   He joked with the hosts about seeking advice on his speech from
radio personalities Dr. Laura Schlessinger, G. Gordon Liddy and Don
Imus, and the raucous group greeted him warmly.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm looking forward to the conversation with America over the
radio airwaves,'' Bush said. ''You're talking to a lot of folks.
... It's a good way to communicate.''
</P>
<P>
   Several hosts in the audience said that while Bush's 10-minute
speech had been entertaining, they didn't learn anything of
substance about his candidacy, and the address probably wouldn't
affect what radio jocks said about his campaign on the air.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I go on the show Monday, I'll be able to say he's funny,
he's charming and he's well prepared,'' said Dan Yorke, of WPRO
radio in Providence, R.I.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
