<HEADLINE> Three arrested in murder of livery driver; 5 more robbedovernight.  </HEADLINE>
o0049nyc--
r n AM-NY--LiveryCab-Attacks 1st-LdWritethru 650 04-29 0678
AM-NY--Livery Cab-Attacks, 1st-Ld Writethru, 650   
Three arrested in murder of livery driver; 5 more robbed
overnight.   
EDS: INSERTS grafs 17-19 to ADD details of slowdown, partition
delays; SUBS 3rd graf to tighten; SUBS 15th graf to tighten; Jenny
Delacruz in the 12th graf is male and reference to him as a him is
cq.
AP Photos, 
By LUKAS I. ALPERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP)-- Three Brooklyn teen-agers were arrested and
charged in connection to the shooting death of livery cab driver
Cesar Lopez, the ninth driver to be killed so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Felicia Fields, 18, Charles Rhodes, 17, and Tyriek Cross, 17,
were all charged with second-degree murder. Lopez, 43, was shot in
the back of his head while in his car in Brooklyn shortly before 4
a.m. Friday, said Sgt. Victor Ramos.
</P>
<P>
   The number of livery drivers killed in the first four months of
the year has almost reached the total number of drivers killed last
year. Eleven drivers were killed in all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez did not have a bulletproof partition in his car, and
police say he had picked up two passengers who hailed him on the
street -- a widespread practice that violates rules for livery
drivers. Livery cabs are supposed to be summoned by a phone call to
the company, unlike regular yellow taxis that are hailed on the
street.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Mateo, president of the New York State Federation of
Taxi Drivers, said the law should be done away with and replaced
with one that makes it mandatory for livery cabs to have
bulletproof partitions
</P>
<P>
   ''It is unfair for a family that lives in the inner city to have
to stand out in the rain and the cold and not be able to hail a
taxi because yellow taxis won't go there,'' Mateo said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact is that people have little choice but to hail these
livery cabs, so let's make it legal to do so and also make it the
law for the cabs to have the partitions.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the arrests, there were also five robberies of
livery cab drivers around the city Friday night and Saturday
morning, police said.
</P>
<P>
   In one case a Brooklyn livery cab driver had a machete held to
his throat during an attempted robbery by two teen-age passengers
early Saturday morning, said police spokesman Alan Krawitz.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, who was not hurt, struggled with the robbers and
held one until authorities arrived. A description of the second
suspect led to his arrest by patrolling officers.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Vargas, 17, and Luis Bello, 18 were charged with robbery
and criminal possession of a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   In another robbery in the Kingsbridge Heights section of the
Bronx, early Saturday, a 35-year-old driver got into dispute with
his passenger, Jenny Delacruz, 24. Delacruz pulled out a black
object, which the driver thought was a gun, and then fled the car.
</P>
<P>
   After the driver radioed his dispatcher, his co-workers gave
chase and caught Delacruz, holding him till police arrived, Krawitz
said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver was taken to the hospital with chest pains. Delacruz
was taken to North Central Bronx hospital with facial abrasions.
</P>
<P>
   Two other robberies occurred in Queens, and one in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   After this year's seventh killing, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
pledged $5 million to help equip the city's livery cars with
bulletproof partitions or digital security cameras. He also
announced the creation of a fund to help the families of slain
drivers.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., asked for $600,000 in
federal funds to purchase 2,000 partitions.
</P>
<P>
   The recent demand for partitions has apparently overwhelmed
shops that install them. The waiting list to have partitions
installed ranges from one week to two months.
</P>
<P>
   Mateo, on Saturday, urged drivers to institute an industry
slowdown until partitions are installed.
</P>
<P>
   The police department has created a task force and assigned 300
officers to protect the city's 41,000 livery drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir on Friday pledged to assign
more officers to the task force. Also, police will set up more
checkpoints where they stop drivers to see if they're OK.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
