<HEADLINE> Peru's Fujimori Agrees to Debate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- President Alberto Fujimori, seeking an
unprecedented third term in office, has agreed to hold a public
debate with his rival in an upcoming runoff presidential vote, his
political party said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Alejandro Toledo's Possible Peru party said it is appointing
three delegates to negotiate details of the debate with
representatives for Fujimori's Peru 2000 movement. The two men have
not debated before.
</P>
<P>
   The National election Board said the date for the decisive
second round of balloting will be announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The runoff was necessary after neither candidate received a
majority of the vote in the April 9 election, although Fujimori was
close with 49.8 percent. Toledo placed a close second, and five
other candidate lagged far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently worried over massive claims of fraud in the April
vote, the influential Roman Catholic Church on Saturday urged,
''for the sake of the well-being of the Peruvian people, a totally
clear electoral process, with respect to ethic demands, truth,
equality of rights for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has threatened to boycott the second round unless what he
called wide-ranging electoral abuses are eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori has denied irregularities and has vowed a clean second
round.
</P>
<P>
   But the results have been questioned by international monitors
and last Tuesday President Clinton signed a congressional
resolution warning that Peru could face political and economic
sanctions if electoral irregularities persist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
