<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 29, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuban-Americans March for Elian
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Tens of thousands of angry Cuban-Americans marched through
Miami's Little Havana today, protesting the raid in which federal agents took
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez from the home of his relatives. Organizers of the
march hoped it would to send a strong but peaceful message to the federal
government. Police stayed visibly distant from the chanting demonstrators. The
boy is now living with his father, stepmother and half brother at the rural Wye
River retreat in Maryland. He must remain in the United States until a federal
appeals court rules on the Miami relatives' bid for him to have an asylum
hearing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Vietnam Marks War's Anniversary
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam (AP) -- From a garrison of sandbags and barbed
wire, a new Vietnam of high-rises and high-tech celebrates the 25th anniversary
of the end of the war in a festival of song, speeches, fashion shows and mass
weddings. Ho Chi Minh City's wide boulevards were bathed in a rainbow of the
bright colors of spring -- red, blue, yellow and purple. Trees, utility poles
and street corners were festooned with the flags of Vietnam and the Communist
Party, and with placards marked in large numbers ''30.4,'' April 30, the day
Saigon died.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Masters Town Hall Meetings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Four hours of voter questions wasn't too much for
Vice President Al Gore, who took on immigration, education, abortion and dozens
of other topics at a record-long town hall meeting. At the meeting late
yesterday in New Mexico, Gore talked to the audience for more than two and a
half hours and then took questions one on one for another hour and a half. Town
hall meetings, long a favorite of President Clinton, have become a staple of
politics, as candidates demonstrate their ability to answer any question on the
spot.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Note Found in Pa. Suspect's Home
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOUNT LEBANON, Pa. (AP) -- Authorities trying to explain what may have
motivated a 34-year-old immigration lawyer to allegedly go on a shooting spree
that left five people dead yesterday say a two-page note found in the man's home
holds some clues. Allegheny County District Attorney Stephen Zappala Jr. refused
to say what the note contained, but he said the words -- believed to have been
