shootings were hate crimes. Five people died in the attacks: a Jewish woman who
lived next door to Baumhammers, an Indian man at a grocery store, two Asian men
in a Chinese restaurant and a black man at a Karate school.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Iraq: Oil Exports To Surpass $8.5B
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Iraq said Saturday it would export more than $8.5
billion worth of oil in its current six-month phase, a record for its earnings
under the U.N. oil-for-food program. In forecasting such high revenue for the
phase ending late May, Iraq also signaled it was implementing part of the U.N.
Security Council resolution it had rejected The announcement was made in a
statement by Oil Minister Amer Mohammed Rashid to the official Iraqi News
Agency. The U.N. program used to limit Iraq to selling $5.2 billion in oil every
six months. Iraq was allowed to exceed the limit only with special dispensation.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Foreigners Seek German Tech Jobs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAMBURG, Germany (AP) -- Foreigners are already jumping at a German proposal
to bring computer experts from abroad to fill high-tech jobs, even though the
plan has yet to be approved, a newspaper said Saturday. Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder last month proposed setting up a green card system similar to that in
the United States to allow up to 20,000 qualified foreigners work in Germany for
up to five years. Technology companies have begged for Schroeder's help to ease
what they say is a 75,000 worker shortfall.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Astros Beat Brewers 10-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Houston took advantage of 14 walks -- including nine by
Everett Stull -- as the Astros beat the Milwaukee Brewers 10-3 despite getting
only five hits. Ken Caminiti went 1-for-3 with four RBIs on a two-run single and
a pair of bases-loaded walks. The two teams combined for 23 walks, including a
franchise record 14 by Milwaukee. The Brewers' previous record was 13 walks --
done four times. Stull (1-2) gave up just one hit in 3 2-3 innings in his major
league debut. But he allowed seven runs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reds Beat Pirates 6-5
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Second baseman Warren Morris's two-base error allowed the
Cincinnati Reds to score the tiebreaking run in the eighth inning of a 6-5 win
over the Pittsburgh Pirates today. After Morris had given the Pirates a 5-4 lead
with a solo homer in the seventh, Jason Christiansen (1-2) walked Sean Casey to
open the eighth and gave up a single to Ken Griffey Jr. The Reds managed just
two hits in the first six innings against Francisco Cordova but rallied for
three runs in the seventh.
</P>
