<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archbishop of Canterbury in Sudan  </HEADLINE>
By MOHAMED OSMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) -- Archbishop of Canterbury George Carey,
the spiritual leader of the Anglican Church, met Saturday with the
government on problems faced by the country's minority Christians,
who have waged a 17-year civil war for more rights.
</P>
<P>
   Carey, who arrived late Friday on a four-day visit, is carrying
a strong message of support and encouragement for the Christians, a
statement issued by Lambeth Palace, the archbishop's office, said.
</P>
<P>
   Sudanese officials said he met with Social Planning Minister
Gotby el-Mahdi for more than 40 minutes. The meeting ''stressed the
importance of dialogue and coexistence between Muslims and
Christians,'' a ministry statement said.
</P>
<P>
   It said the two reviewed ''peace issues in Sudan as well as the
negative aspects of the (civil) war and the exodus of citizens to
the north.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday, Carey led prayers at camp on the outskirts of
the capital, Khartoum, for refugees displaced by the civil war.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 2 million people have died in fighting and
accompanying famines since rebels from the predominantly Christian
and animist south took up arms in 1983 to press for autonomy from
the Muslim-dominated north. Christians form 16 percent of Sudan's
29 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Carey also met with Foreign Minister Mustafa
Osman Ismail, but no details were available.
</P>
<P>
   The visit is Carey's third to Sudan since he became head of the
Anglican Church in 1991. On previous visits he has condemned
discrimination against Sudan's Christian communities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
