<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diamondbacks 7, Cubs 4  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY ARMOUR, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Pinch-hitter Erubiel Durazo drove in the
game-winner with a two-run single in the 10th inning Saturday as
the Arizona Diamondbacks beat the Chicago Cubs 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied at 4, Durazo grounded a 2-2 pitch just past
first baseman Mark Grace's outstretched hand and into the outfield,
scoring Bernard Gilkey and Kelly Stinnett.
</P>
<P>
   And the Diamondbacks weren't done. Rick Aguilera walked Hanley
Frias and Jay Bell to force in another run.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks wouldn't have even needed Durazo's extra-inning
heroics, but Henry Rodriguez hit a pinch-hit, two-run homer in the
bottom of the ninth off Matt Mantei (1-0) to tie the game at 4. It
was Rodriguez's seventh homer of the season, and they've all come
in the last 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Morgan pitched the 10th for his fourth save.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Colbrunn had given the Diamondbacks almost all of the
offense they needed, hitting a solo homer and driving in another
run. He went 4-for-4 and came within a double of hitting for the
cycle.
</P>
<P>
   Colbrunn had a chance at the cycle in the eighth inning, but
Cubs reliever Brian Williams walked him on a 3-2 count. He got
another chance in the 10th, but fell short with another single. It
was the fifth four-hit game of Colbrunn's career.
</P>
<P>
   After Rodriguez tied the game, Colbrunn led off the 10th with a
single off Mark Guthrie (2-2) and was then replaced by the swifter
Travis Lee, who moved to second on Steve Finley's sacrifice bunt.
Mark Guthrie walked Bernard Gilkey intentionally, and then got in
trouble when he skipped his fifth pitch to Kelly Stinnett in the
dirt.
</P>
<P>
   The ball hit the edge of the plate and took a wild bounce,
allowing Lee and Gilkey to advance. Guthrie then walked Stinnett
intentionally, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   That was it for Guthrie, who was replaced by Rick Aguilera. The
Cubs got Lee out at home on a fielder's choice, but Joe Girardi's
throw back to first wasn't in time and pinch-hitter Lenny Harris
reached to keep the bases loaded for Durazo.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Anderson and the Diamondbacks had kept the Cubs in check
all game, allowing just two extra-base hits in the first eight
innings. But trailing 4-2 with one out, Girardi reached when Luis
Gonzalez dropped what should have been a routine catch.
</P>
<P>
   That was it for Anderson, who gave up three runs -- two of them
earned -- and eight hits in 8 1-3 innings. Mantei came in to
relieve, and Rodriguez didn't waste much time taking him deep.
</P>
<P>
   He put a 2-1 pitch into the backdrop in center field, tying the
game at 4. It was only the second pinch-hit homer of his career,
and the Cubs' first pinch-hit home run of the season.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Young stole his 300th base Saturday, stealing third in the
first inning. Young has five stolen bases so far this season. ...
Gutierrez, who leads the majors in sacrifice bunts, got his ninth
in the first inning. That's the most for a Cub position player
since Doug Glanville's nine sac bunts in all of 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
