<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 29, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuban-Americans March Peacefully for Elian
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Cuban-Americans still angry over last week's early morning
seizure of Elian Gonzalez from the home of his Miami relatives marched
peacefully through Miami's Little Havana today, hoping to send a strong message
to the federal government. Police stayed visibly distant from the chanting
demonstrators, many of whom carried signs denouncing President Clinton and
Attorney General Janet Reno for taking Elian from his Miami relatives and
sending him to his Cuban father. The boy is now living with his father,
stepmother and half brother at the rural Wye River retreat in Maryland. He must
remain in the United States until a federal appeals court rules on the Miami
relatives' bid for him to have an asylum hearing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Optimistic About McCain Meeting
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Texas Gov. George Bush said today he hopes to find common
ground with defeated presidential rival John McCain in a meeting McCain almost
canceled because of disagreements over the agenda. Bush would like to gain the
support of his still popular primary opponent, who has not endorsed the
presumptive Republican nominee. McCain and his advisers were irritated by Bush's
announcement that he would ask the Arizona senator in their first face-to-face
meeting since the primaries whether he was willing to serve as vice president.
McCain has said repeatedly that he doesn't want the job.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Note Found in Pa. Suspect's Home
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOUNT LEBANON, Pa. (AP) -- Authorities trying to explain what may have
motivated a 34-year-old immigration lawyer to allegedly go on a shooting spree
that left five people dead yesterday say a two-page note found in the man's home
holds some clues. Allegheny County District Attorney Stephen Zappala Jr. refused
to say what the note contained, but he said the words -- believed to have been
typed by suspect Scott Baumhammers -- are relevant to determining whether the
shootings were hate crimes. Five people died in the attacks.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
New Vietnam Marks War's Anniversary
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam (AP) -- From a garrison of sandbags and barbed
wire, a new Vietnam of high-rises and high-tech celebrates the 25th anniversary
of the end of the war in a festival of song, speeches, fashion shows and mass
weddings. Ho Chi Minh City's wide boulevards were bathed in a rainbow of the
bright colors of spring -- red, blue, yellow and purple. Trees, utility poles
and street corners were festooned with the flags of Vietnam and the Communist
Party, and with placards marked in large numbers ''30.4,'' April 30, the day
Saigon died.
</P>
