<HEADLINE> AM-NY--Arsenic Poisoning,1st Ld-Writethru,0398  </HEADLINE>
Former doctor indicted in wife's poisoning
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- A former plastic surgeon has been indicted
in the attempted murder of his estranged wife by arsenic poisoning,
his chief attorney confirmed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Joel L. Daniels told The Buffalo News that prosecutors
have advised him of the indictment in the 1999 poisoning of Deborah
Pignataro, 42, who is in a wheelchair with aftereffects of the
poisoning. He did not reveal the specific felony charges lodged by
a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Erie County District Attorney Frank J. Clark refused comment on
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels confirmed that Anthony Pignataro, also 42, did not
testify before the grand jury about the arsenic poisoning that
hospitalized the West Seneca housewife for two months and injured
their adolescent son and daughter. Daniels said he expects a court
arraignment within the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have consistently maintained that there is no case, and
we're going to fight this indictment and try to get it thrown out
because we believe there isn't any real proof, only imaginary
proof,'' the attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a week, Pignataro has been serving time in Elmira
Correctional Facility for drinking and using heroin in violation of
probation. He is being held in the reception area while state
prison officials determine where he will serve his current term.
</P>
<P>
   Pignataro lost his medical license over the death of a cosmetic
surgery patient three years ago during a procedure in his office.
</P>
<P>
   On March 13, State Supreme Court Justice Ronald H. Tills ordered
Pignataro to begin a 16-month to four-year prison term on probation
violation charges stemming from the four-month jail term he imposed
two years ago for the death of his patient.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted in the arsenic matter, Pignataro would face an
additional prison term of up to another 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Pignataro and his estranged wife of 15 years both still face a
joint child-neglect trial in Erie County Family Court in June for
allegedly exposing their children to arsenic last year.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe a bowl of soup that immediately sickened
Mrs. Pignataro and her young daughter during the summer of 1999 may
have been of many arsenic-laced meals Mr. Pignataro served.
</P>
<P>
   West Seneca is seven miles east of Buffalo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
