<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIA Said To Know of Bay of Pigs Leak  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The CIA was aware that the Soviet Union found
out the date of the failed U.S.-backed Bay of Pigs invasion of Cuba
more than a week before it took place on April 17, 1961, but went
ahead with the operation anyway, newly declassified intelligence
documents show.
</P>
<P>
   Previously released Soviet documents indicated that Moscow had
learned some details of the operation ahead of time, but the report
from the Taylor Commission shows for the first time that the CIA
knew about the leak and proceeded with the invasion, said Peter
Kornbluh, a senior analyst with the nonprofit National Security
Archive.
</P>
<P>
   Portions of the Taylor Commission report had been released in
1977 and 1986. The latest release, which shows newly declassified
information, was supposed to be made public in 1996, but was only
released recently following a bureaucratic mix-up.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was some indication that the Soviets somewhere around
the 9th (of April) had gotten the date of the 17th,'' Jacob
Esterline, the CIA operations official who headed the task force
responsible for coordinating the invasion, testified at a May 1961
commission meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''But there was no indication at any time that they had any idea
where the operation was going to take place,'' Esterline added.
</P>
<P>
   It is unknown exactly how the Soviets found out, but Esterline
said it was not from the Cuban exiles since the exiles were not
briefed on when the invasion would take place until April 12.
</P>
<P>
   Kornbluh said there also was no indication that the CIA informed
President Kennedy of the leak before the invasion took place.
</P>
<P>
   The documents show that CIA director Allen W. Dulles, three
weeks after the failed operation, questioned the agency's role in
future paramilitary operations.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm the first to recognize that I don't think that the CIA
should run paramilitary operations of the type in Cuba,'' Dulles
told the commission. He added that ''the Cuban operation has had a
very serious effect on all our work'' and ''I think we should limit
ourselves more to secret intelligence collection and operations of
the nonmilitary category.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Kornbluh, the report also shows that CIA official
Frank Egan, who was in charge of the training camps in Guatemala,
told the commission Cuban leader Fidel Castro had infiltrated four
double agents into the camp.
</P>
<P>
   Although CIA officials limited mail going into and out of the
camp in the weeks leading up the official, Egan said the double
agents apparently got information out to Castro.
</P>
<P>
   The Taylor Commission report is the second government report
made public on the Bay of Pigs. Kornbluh said he filed a Freedom of
Information Act request for the third document, by a CIA historian,
but it has yet to be released.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 1946 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000429.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stanford Wins Distance Medley  </HEADLINE>
By CHUCK SCHOFFNER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Stanford got the victory it wanted at
the Drake Relays and Suzy Favor Hamilton got her record -- and a
world best to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointed after second-place finishes in two relays on
Friday, Stanford came back with a vengeance to win the distance
medley Saturday behind a brilliant anchor from Gabe Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings covered the final 1,600 meters in 3 minutes, 56.5
seconds -- the equivalent of a 3:57.6 mile -- to blow away Tulsa,
Arizona and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ''We came here thinking we were the bomb and we know that,''
Jennings said. ''But things didn't fall into our hands. But we know
who we are. I went to the other guys and was like 'Hey, you know
who you are, man. Remember that.'
</P>
<P>
   ''I think today was an example of remembering that, how good we
really are and can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's redemption came on a breezy, sunny day before a
sellout crowd of 18,000 that saw Favor Hamilton win the 1,500
meters with the fastest time in the world this year by a woman.
</P>
<P>
   Favor Hamilton, competing at that distance for the first time in
14 months, ran her race in 4:05.13, well under the old Drake record
of 4:10.89 by Cindy Bremser in 1985. She had surgery to repair a
torn Achilles' tendon on April 19, 1999, and had not run since
winning the 1,500 at the U.S. indoor championships in early March
of last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really wanted to get the record and I'm glad I got the
record by five seconds,'' Favor Hamilton said. ''This was a good
stepping stone for me before the Olympic trials. The race felt so
easy. I'm just anxious to see what I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The meet's final day also produced a victory by local favorite
Joey Woody in the 400 hurdles and sub-4-minute miles by Clyde
Colenso and Paul McMullen.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings, the NCAA indoor mile champion, was 15 meters off the
lead in the medley when he got the baton after Ryan Carroll's 800.
He made up the gap quickly and settled into third place behind
Tulsa's Dwight Davis and Arizona's Chris Schaefer.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with 1{ laps to go, Jennings blew past Davis and Schaefer
on the backstretch and they had no answer as he built his lead.
Stanford finished in 9:32.86 to win easily, while Tulsa ran 9:40.17
and Arizona 9:42.53.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was like, 'You're feeling it Jennings, you're feeling it
Jennings.' And sure enough, I was feeling it,'' Jennings said.
''When you should be feeling it and you are, things are going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Stember ran the opening 1,200 for Stanford and Mark
Hassell did the 400. Stember and Jennings ran on the Stanford
distance medley team that set a world indoor record at the NCAA
meet this year, and the Cardinal had expected to dominate the
distance relays in this meet.
</P>
<P>
   But they were upset by Northern Iowa in the 6,400 Friday and
Stember couldn't hold off Missouri's Derrick Peterson in the 3,200
relay.
</P>
<P>
   ''We had a lot of motivation from yesterday,'' Carroll said.
''We just wanted to put it away and have no questions we're one of
the best programs out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Woody, a former Northern Iowa runner who was sixth in the world
championships last year, beat a strong field that included 1996
Olympic gold medalist Derrick Adkins and defending NCAA champion
Bayano Kamani of Baylor.
</P>
<P>
   With a good start, Woody made up the stagger by the second turn,
took the lead on the backstretch and held it, finishing in 48.88.
Woody had lost to Adkins last year after winning in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't want to come back here and lose again, that's for
sure,'' he said. ''I was just happy to be able to come out and do
something for the fans, get a little revenge for myself, I guess.
Great field they put together, so I was happy about that. It made
me really work hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Sherman Armstrong of Illinois was second in 49.20 and Adkins was
third in 49.99. Kamani ran 51.02 to finish fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Colenso, a former SMU runner, pulled away from McMullen in the
straightaway to win the mile in 3:59.71. McMullen, the 1998 winner,
was timed in 3:59.97.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's JaWarren Hooker won the 100 (10.28) and the 200
(20.63), and Baylor won the 1,600 relay for the ninth straight year
in 3:05.33. Brandon Counts brought the Bears from 7 meters down
against Oklahoma and anchored in 45.5 after running a 44.2-second
400 in the sprint medley relay.
</P>
<P>
   High jumper Hollis Conway, a two-time Olympic medalist for the
United States, announced his retirement from the sport after
finishing seventh at 6 feet, 9 inches. Conway, the American
collegiate record-holder, won a silver medal in the 1988 Olympics
and a bronze in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's Ashley Wysong outran Stanford freshman Lindsay Hyatt
in the final 100 meters to give the Tigers a victory in the women's
3,200 relay in 8:34.76, the fastest time this year by a college
team.
</P>
<P>
   Korene Hinds and Amy Mortimer, who finished 1-2 in the 3,000
meters at the NCAA indoor meet this year, gave Kansas State
consecutive victories.
</P>
<P>
   Hinds passed Nebraska's Liz Biehl and Arizona's Cara Cline in
the final 20 meters for a victory in the sprint medley relay. She
ran her 800 leg in 2:05.6 as the Wildcats finished in 3:50.62.
</P>
<P>
   In the very next event, Mortimer won the 5,000 in 16:14.57 -- the
first time she had ever run the race -- after overcoming a spill
that resulted in a restart and left her with a nasty bruise and
scrape on her left shoulder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 1959 </TRAILER>
