<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Today In History  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Today is Sunday, April 30, the 121st day of 2000.
There are 245
days left in the year.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's Highlight in History:
</P>
<P>
   One hundred years ago, on April 30, 1900, a legend was born as
engineer John Luther ''Casey'' Jones of the Illinois Central
Railroad died in a wreck near Vaughan, Miss., after staying at the
controls in an effort to save the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   On this date:
</P>
<P>
   In 1789, George Washington took office in New York as the first
president of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1803, the United States purchased the Louisiana Territory
from France.
</P>
<P>
   In 1812, Louisiana became the 18th state of the Union.
</P>
<P>
   In 1900, Hawaii was organized as a U.S. territory.
</P>
<P>
   In 1939, the New York World's Fair officially opened.
</P>
<P>
   In 1945, as Russian troops approached his Berlin bunker, Adolf
Hitler committed suicide along with his wife of one day, Eva Braun.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, President Nixon announced the United States was sending
troops into Cambodia, an action that sparked widespread protest.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, President Nixon announced the resignations of top aides
H.R. Haldeman and John Ehrlichman, along with Attorney General
Richard G. Kleindienst and White House counsel John Dean.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, the South Vietnamese capital of Saigon fell to
Communist forces.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, an estimated 125,000 people died as a cyclone struck
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago: Hostage Frank Reed was released by his captives
in Lebanon, the second American freed in eight days.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago: More than 10,000 soldiers, students and children
in Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam, celebrated the 20th anniversary of
the end of the war. President Clinton announced he would end U.S.
trade and investment with Iran, denouncing the Tehran government as
''inspiration and paymaster to terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   One year ago: A bomb exploded at a gay pub in London, killing
three people and injuring more than 70. The Rev. Jesse Jackson met
with three U.S. soldiers being held prisoner by Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Birthdays: Princess Juliana of the Netherlands is 91.
Actor Al Lewis is 90. Actress Cloris Leachman is 74. Singer Willie
Nelson is 67. Talk show host Gary Collins is 62. Actor Burt Young
is 60. Singer Bobby Vee is 57. Actress Jill Clayburgh is 56. Movie
director Allan Arkush is 52. Actor Perry King is 52. Singer Merrill
Osmond is 47. Movie director Jane Campion is 46. Actor Paul Gross
is 41. Basketball player Isiah Thomas is 39. Country musician
Robert Reynolds (The Mavericks) is 38. Rapper Turbo B (Snap) is 33.
Rock musician Clark Vogeler (Toadies) is 31. Rhythm-and-blues
singer Chris ''Choc'' Dalyrimple (Soul For Real) is 29. Rock singer
J.R. Richards (Dishwalla) is 28. Rhythm-and-blues singer Jeff
Timmons (98 Degrees) is 27. Actor Johnny Galecki is 25. Actress
Kirsten Dunst is 18. Country singer Tyler Wilkinson (The
Wilkinsons) is 16.
</P>
<P>
   Thought for Today: ''More persons, on the whole, are humbugged
by believing nothing, than by believing too much.'' -- P.T. Barnum,
American showman (1810-1891).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 2001 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000429.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 29, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cuba Keeps Up Fight for Elian Return
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Pressing a national campaign to return Elian Gonzalez to his
communist homeland, thousands of government supporters rallied today in central
Cuba to protest the boy's continued stay in the United States. The rally came as
tens of thousands of Cuban-Americans were winding up a very different kind of
march in Miami -- one protesting the U.S. government raid a week before that
seized Elian from his Miami relatives and reunited him with his father in
Washington. Elian and his father Juan are to stay in the United States pending a
May 11 hearing by a federal appeals court in Atlanta on the Miami relatives'
request for a hearing on whether to grant political asylum to the child.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mich. Man Kills Wife, 2 Others, Self
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) -- A man apparently distraught over his wife's
decision to leave him shot and killed her and two others and then killed
himself, authorities said. The woman, who had left her husband several days
earlier, returned to the couple's home outside Detroit with her sister and her
sister's boyfriend this afternoon. Believing they had a hostage situation,
police tried to negotiate with the gunman for several hours but got no response.
About five hours after the boyfriend was shot, SWAT team members saw the bodies
of the gunman and his wife through a back window of the home. The woman's sister
was found dead nearby.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Vietnam Marks End of War Anniversary
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam (AP) -- Twenty-five years after the end of the war,
a new Vietnam full of high rises and technology celebrated the toppling of
U.S.-back South Vietnam with a festival of song, speeches, fashion shows and
mass weddings. America's direct military intervention in Vietnam ended on Jan.
27, 1973, when Washington and Hanoi signed the Paris Peace Agreement. While it
brought an end to America's longest and most divisive war, the fighting never
stopped for the Vietnamese.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bush Looking Forward To McCain Meeting
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Presidential hopeful George W. Bush said he is looking
forward to discussing a wide range of issues with former rival John McCain. Bush
would like to gain the support of his defeated but still popular primary
opponent, who has not endorsed the presumptive Republican nominee. An agenda
agreed upon by the two campaigns on Friday was said to include McCain's
signature issue of campaign finance overhaul along with military reform, social
security, education, health care, making the GOP more inclusive and McCain's
role in the fall campaign and the Republican National Convention.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
CIA Said To Know of Bay of Pigs Leak
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The CIA was aware that the Soviet Union found out the date
of the failed U.S.-backed Bay of Pigs invasion of Cuba more than a week before
it took place, but went ahead with the operation anyway, newly declassified
intelligence documents show. Previously released Soviet documents indicated that
Moscow had learned some details of the operation ahead of time, but the report
from the Taylor Commission shows for the first time that the CIA knew about the
leak and proceeded with the invasion. The latest release, which shows newly
declassified information, was supposed to be made public in 1996, but was only
released recently following a bureaucratic mix-up.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Physicists Recalculate Earth's Mass
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Using a new, precise measurement of the force of
gravity, physicists have recalculated the mass of the Earth and determined the
planet is a bit lighter than previously thought. The new estimate is that the
third rock from the sun has a mass of 5.972 sextillion metric tons, or 5,972
followed by 18 zeros. Textbooks currently list the mass at 5.978 sextillion
metric tons.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Diamondbacks Beat Cubs 7-4
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Pinch-hitter Erubiel Durazo drove in the game-winner with a
two-run single in the 10th inning today as the Arizona Diamondbacks beat the
Chicago Cubs 7-4. With the game tied at 4, Durazo grounded a 2-2 pitch just past
first baseman Mark Grace's outstretched hand and into the outfield, scoring
Bernard Gilkey and Kelly Stinnett. Greg Colbrunn had given the Diamondbacks
almost all of the offense they needed, hitting a solo homer and driving in
another run.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Giants Beat Expos 2-1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Barry Bonds and the San Francisco Giants finally made
themselves at home in their new ballpark. Bonds led off the eighth inning with
his ninth home run of the season and the Giants beat the Montreal Expos 2-1
today for their first win in seven games at Pacific Bell Park. The Giants were
the first team to lose six straight games to start its stay in a newly
constructed facility. The expansion New York Mets dropped their first seven
games at the old Polo Grounds in 1962.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by PAULINE M. MILLARD
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
