<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ladies Din Wins S.F. Breeders' Cup  </HEADLINE>
By DENNIS GEORGATOS, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, Calif. (AP) -- In a seemingly never-ending trip, Ladies
Din finally came home a winner.
</P>
<P>
   Running on a sixth different race course in six starts and just
a month removed from a grueling trip to the Middle East, Ladies Din
rallied through the stretch to beat Fighting Falcon by a head in
the $300,000 San Francisco Breeders' Cup Mile Handicap at Golden
Gate Fields on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got a tremendous turn of foot. He's a big, tall,
beautiful horse. He was conditioned perfectly. He was just primed
for today and it showed,'' said Kent Desormeaux, who rode the
6-year-old gelding to its ninth career victory in 26 starts.
However, it was the horse's first win in 11 starts since the Oct.
22, 1998, Oak Tree Derby at Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   Ladies Din covered the mile on the turf in 1:35.46 and earned a
first prize of $150,000, boosting the former claimer's career
earnings to $1,188,304. It was the first race for Ladies Din since
a fifth-place finish March 25 in the $2 million Dubai Duty Free, a
1 1-8 mile turf race in the United Arab Emirates.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Schiappa of Las Vegas, who owns the horse in partnership
with J. Terrance Lanni, said he didn't have concerns about running
the Los Angeles-based Ladies Din so soon after the overseas trip.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would never have run if he wasn't ready to run,'' Schiappa
said. ''He's an animal. He thrives on this. I'm just happy he won.
This guy is my pet.''
</P>
<P>
   Schiappa bought Ladies Din out of a $32,000 claiming race at Del
Mar on July 30, 1997. Ladies Din won that race as a 16-to-1 shot
and Schiappa came away with $35,000 in winnings from bets he placed
in addition to claiming the horse.
</P>
<P>
   ''You got him for free,'' Desormeaux joked.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Julio Canani, who won the San Francisco mile for the
fourth time, said Ladies Din let him know all along that his
travels -- the horse has run in Dubai, Kentucky and four different
California tracks in the last eight months -- wouldn't pose a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''When he got off the plane from Dubai, he acted just like a
3-year-old,'' Canani said. ''I told the owners you may think I'm
crazy, but I'm going to run him right back. I don't think it's a
rule all horses have to be affected by an overseas trip. Some may
take two, three or four months but others might bounce right back.
They're all different and I could tell this one was handling it
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux said Ladies Din has been running and coming up just
short against some of the top turf horses in the country but a
return to its favored mile distance coupled with some easier
competition made a difference.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was absolutely no difference from how he ran last time
and today. He was full of himself in Dubai,'' Desormeaux said. ''He
ran his guts out. It was just an eighth of a mile too far. A mile
was perfect for him. This guy will give anybody a race at a mile.''
</P>
<P>
   Ladies Din returned $6.20, $3.20 and $2.60 as the 2-to-1
favorite in the 10-horse field. Fighting Falcon paid $3.60 and
$3.20, and Self Feeder returned $4.40 to show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
