<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Diary Said To Oppose Crockett Lore  </HEADLINE>
By AMY STRAHAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) --A diary account claiming that Davy Crockett
was captured and executed at the Battle of the Alamo -- contrary to
Texas folklore -- seems to be authentic, one of the state's leading
archivists said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The diary was written by Lt. Col. Jose Enrique de la Pena, who
served in Santa Anna's army and fought at the Alamo during Texas'
war for independence.
</P>
<P>
   The diary's account of Crockett's death states that he and six
other defenders were captured and executed shortly after the battle
-- a claim that prompted an indignant response from patriotic Texans
after it was first translated in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Legend has long held that the coonskin-capped Crockett fended
off Mexican soldiers with his long-rifle ''Betsy'' during a 13-day
siege before dying near the front doors of the Alamo's chapel on
March 6, 1836.
</P>
<P>
   The facts suggest that the diary is authentic, not a forgery, as
some detractors have claimed, said David Gracy, a University of
Texas archivist studying the book.
</P>
<P>
   Historians gathered Saturday for a panel discussion of the
controversial diary. Alumni purchased the diary and gave it to UT
more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''My colleagues and I were given permission to test the document
in any way we can,'' Gracy said, adding that he has had only three
weeks so far to evaluate it. But so far, the results seem positive,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gracy said the book's paper is consistent with the materials of
the period, and added that watermarks throughout the 680-page
document appear to be authentic.
</P>
<P>
   ''These facts suggest strongly that this person had access to
paper from the Mexican army,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other archivists said Saturday that Pena's account of Crockett's
death is consistent with that of other eyewitnesses.
</P>
<P>
   And they emphasized that the hero's capture shouldn't detract
from his legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''De la Pena doesn't say Crockett surrendered,'' said Tom
Kreneck, curator of Special Collections and Archives at Texas A&AMP;M
in Corpus Christi. ''It said he was captured and executed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 2107 </TRAILER>
