<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kings Ass't Coach Has Heart Attack  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Basketball Hall of Famer Pete Carril,
an assistant coach with the Sacramento Kings the last four seasons,
had a minor heart attack Saturday, according to team physician Dr.
Jeff Tanji.
</P>
<P>
   Carril, 69, was taken to Sutter General Hospital around 10 a.m.
because he was not feeling well, and was later transferred to
Sutter Memorial Hospital. Both medical centers are in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Tanji said Carril had complained of chest pains and was
diagnosed as being in the early stages of a minor heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   Carril, who was inducted into the Basketball Hall of Fame in
1997, was expected to remain at the hospital until next week in
order to get rest and undergo more diagnostic tests, Tanji said.
Carril was listed in stable condition Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are all greatly relieved that Pete received successful
treatment,'' said Geoff Petrie, Kings vice president of basketball
operations, who played under Carril at Princeton. ''Visiting with
Pete earlier today I can assure you his spirits are good. We're
looking forward to his speedy recovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Carril retired from college coaching in 1996 after one season at
Lehigh and 24 at Princeton. He compiled a 525-273 collegiate record
that included 13 Ivy League championships, 10 seasons of 20 wins or
more, 11 NCAA tournament appearances, and a 1975 NIT championship.
In Carril's final college victory, Princeton upset defending
national champion UCLA 43-41 in the 1996 NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings trail the Los Angeles Lakers 2-0 in their best-of-five
opening-round NBA playoff series. Game 3 is Sunday at Sacramento.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 2132 </TRAILER>
