<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NY Mayor To Decide on Senate Run  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEEKTOWAGA, N.Y. (AP) -- New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
who announced last week he has prostate cancer, says he will decide
by the end of May whether to continue his Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's presence in the race has been the only major threat
to first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's first bid for public office.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being hit with the news of his cancer Thursday, both
candidates spent Saturday courting the Independence Party, New
York's wing of the national Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   Courting third parties is a political necessity in a state where
major party candidates can also run on third-party ballot lines,
but it's also risky business for both Clinton and Giuliani
considering the Reform Party's flirtation with Pat Buchanan as its
presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton flatly told party members on Saturday she wouldn't share
a ticket with the conservative commentator.
</P>
<P>
   ''I cannot and will not, as the price for any endorsement,
embrace or excuse those who use hateful rhetoric to separate and
divide,'' she told about 100 members of the Independence Party at a
forum for Senate candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who waited until Friday before agreeing to appear at
Saturday's event, also has concerns about the strong influence of
Lenora Fulani, a leader of the left-wing New Alliance Party, on the
Independence Party. In a strange political marriage, the
left-leaning Fulani is backing Buchanan's presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's completely up in the air,'' party official Frank MacKay
said Saturday of the feelings within the party about who the Senate
candidate should be. The Independence Party's state convention will
be held in late May or early June.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was Giuliani's second day of campaigning since
announcing Thursday that medical tests showed he had prostate
cancer. The cancer was detected early and was treatable, he said,
but that treatment could mean giving up the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has already cut back on his schedule to fit in more
medical appointments, though he told Republicans in Saratoga
Springs and voters in Buffalo this week that he wants to stay in
the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like to run, I'm prepared to do it ... but there's
this other thing that I have to consider,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Independence Party, with more than 172,471 members, is the
state's third largest party, followed by the Conservative Party,
with 171,496 members. Both are dwarfed by the Democratic, which has
4.96 million members, and the Republican party with 3.09 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a new poll found Giuliani and Clinton in a
statistical dead heat in their race and that the mayor received no
''sympathy bounce'' from his announcement that he has cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Post/Fox TV poll of 601 likely voters from around
the state was conducted by Zogby International Friday night and
Saturday. Asked who they would vote for in a race between Giuliani
and Clinton, 43 percent said the mayor and 43 percent picked
Clinton. Most polls conducted before the cancer announcement also
had the pair running even.
</P>
<P>
   The latest poll had a margin of error of 4 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
