<DOCNO> APW20000429.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecumenical Patriarch Observes Easter  </HEADLINE>
By HARMONIE TOROS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- The spiritual leader of the world's
Orthodox Christians celebrated Easter in a candlelit midnight
ceremony in Istanbul on Sunday in front of an unusually large crowd
of worshippers -- mostly Greeks attracted by the recent
rapprochement between Turkey and Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Bus loads of Greek faithful filled the patriarchate, on the
shore of Istanbul's Golden Horn, leaving many outside its gates
during the procession led by Ecumenical Patriarch Bartholomew I.
</P>
<P>
   ''Christ has risen,'' the patriarch told a crowd of 2,000 people
as the bells of the gold-encrusted Cathedral of St. George chimed.
</P>
<P>
   Only a few hundred people attended the Easter ceremony at the
patriarchate last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was afraid to come here before,'' admitted Katerina Hoidou,
who came with her family from the Greek city of Salonika. ''Now
that the relations are better I decided to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between regional rivals Greece and Turkey have
steadily improved since deadly earthquakes struck Turkey and Greece
last year, leading both peoples to rush aid to each other. The
governments have since pledged to find solutions to their
long-standing disputes -- including territorial disputes in the
Aegean and the division of Cyprus -- which brought the countries to
the brink of war three times in the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The rapprochement gave Hoidou the chance she had been dreaming
of, both as a Greek and as an Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am happy. First of all because this is the church of the
patriarch and because this city is a symbol of Greeks,'' said
Hoidou. Istanbul was the capital of the Greek Byzantine empire
until the Ottoman Turks stormed its gates in 1453. Many Greeks
still call the city by its Greek name, Constantinople.
</P>
<P>
   Easter, the anniversary of the resurrection of Jesus Christ, is
observed by the world's 200 million Orthodox on Sunday. Roman
Catholics and Protestants celebrate Easter a week earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Bartholomew is considered the first among equals of Orthodox
patriarchs. The Orthodox Church and Roman Catholic Church split in
the Great Schism of 1054.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgarian and Romanian Orthodox believers also came to Istanbul
to attend the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very special ceremony with very special feelings,''
said Nicola Gerginsky, a Bulgarian designer from Plovdiv.
</P>
<P>
   Even a bomb attack late Friday that damaged the Turkish Orthodox
Ayayani Church in Istanbul did not affect the crowd. Police defused
two other bombs, one thrown at the church and another in a school
run by the patriarchate, the Anatolia news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Police increased security around churches throughout the city
and policemen stood guard outside the patriarchate during the
celebrations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 2137 </TRAILER>
