<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Masters Town Hall Meetings  </HEADLINE>
By LAURA MECKLER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore explained his
views on any issue put to him as he wooed voters at a town hall
meeting Saturday, one questioner at a time.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gore's second session with voters in two days. Many
questions were friendly, offering the presumptive Democratic
presidential nominee the chance to agree with his inquisitors.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he said, the Senate ought to pass the Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty. Yes, it's crucial to fight for Hispanic needs. No, he
said, putting drug addicts in jail isn't enough -- treatment is also
needed.
</P>
<P>
   But the meetings also gave several hundred voters the chance to
see Gore up close and at length.
</P>
<P>
   One man asked what it meant to be authentic, and Gore responded
with an analysis of why his campaign struggled last fall. The
problem, he said, was acting too much like a vice president and not
enough like a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I made a change,'' he said. ''I started answering questions
without waiting to analyze what the (administration's) agenda
was.''
</P>
<P>
   William Grimes told Gore that his credibility on campaign
fiannce reform was tainted by his raising money at a Buddist temple
and asked the vice president to give him one example showing
''political courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore reponded with a handful of examples, including his support
for the Persian Gulf War in the Senate when many fellow Democrats
did not and his role in helping fashion a compromise on the MX
missile years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   One girl wanted to know if his job was hard.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes it's hard, but if you believe in what you're doing
then hard work is like fun,'' he said. He added: ''Sometimes the
hours are long.''
</P>
<P>
   The hours were certainly long a day earlier in Albuquerque,
N.M., where participants in a town meeting kept him answering
questions for four hours, a personal record. He didn't finish until
11:15 p.m. local time -- or 1:15 a.m. on his body clock.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got to commend your stamina,'' said Roy T. Johnson Jr. as
Gore wrapped things up. ''I can't believe how well you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Town hall meetings, long a favorite of President Clinton, have
become a staple of politics, as candidates demonstrate their
ability to answer any question on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore seems to have mastered the art, displaying the
knowledge of some of the most obscure topics, bantering over who
has the smartest grandson, and steering clear of answers that could
come back to haunt him.
</P>
<P>
   In Albuquerque, Gore agreed with one man that not enough gets
done in Washington but disagreed that eliminating political parties
was the answer.
</P>
<P>
   He agreed that more money is needed for health research, but he
declined to endorse a request for a huge increase on diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   And when a man in black leather began explaining the benefits of
drug legalization, Gore shot back, ''I'm not for it,'' a response
that was met with applause from the audience and mock relief from
press aides.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't always win over his questioner.
</P>
<P>
   Jessica McKenzie, 17, asked him about abortion: ''Why is it
illegal to kill a baby five seconds after it's born and not illegal
five seconds before it's born?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore began on safe ground: ''Didn't she do a good job of
presenting her point of view?'' he asked the crowd, which agreed
that she had. He then briefly defended his position that women
should be allowed to choose abortion, but he spent more time
emphasizing that everyone wants to reduce the number of abortions.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he avoided the question,'' Jessica said later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-29-00 2200 </TRAILER>
