<DOCNO> APW20000429.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devils 1, Maple Leafs 0  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Martin Brodeur stopped 20 Toronto shots as the
New Jersey Devils evened their second-round playoff series, which
has become a battle of goalies.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Joseph stopped every shot he saw, but was helplessly
screened when Colin White scored the lone goal Saturday night in
New Jersey's 1-0 victory in Game 2 of the best-of-seven Eastern
Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The series switches to New Jersey for games 3 and 4, Monday and
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph, coming off a 32-save performance in Game 1, was the most
tested of the two goalies as Toronto was outshot 33-20. He kept the
Maple Leafs in the game but didn't get any help from a Toronto
offense that had trouble breaking the Devils' heavily-fortified
defensive system.
</P>
<P>
   Protecting their first-period lead, the Devils played with three
and four men stacked across the neutral zone for much of the third
period.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's best chance came four minutes into the game when
Wendel Clark broke in alone only to shoot the puck into Brodeur's
chest. The Leafs were unlucky when Tomas Kaberle's shot from the
blue line was deflected on the way to the net and bounced off the
post.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto also squandered a four-minute power-play in the third
period after Jason Arnott drew a double-minor for high-sticking.
The Leafs failed to get a shot on net and have managed just two
goals on 32 power-play chances in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils penalty killers have allowed only one goal in 23
short-handed situations this postseason. Brodeur recorded his
seventh career playoff shutout and first this year.
</P>
<P>
   The loss ended Toronto's three-game playoff winning streak, and
was the first the Maple Leafs in five postseason home games.
</P>
<P>
   The Maple Leafs continue to have trouble starting sharply as
they have yet to score a first-period goal in their eight playoff
games.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils ended a six-game winless streak (0-5-1) against the
Maple Leafs, going back to the 1998-99 regular season.
</P>
<P>
   White, with his first career playoff goal, scored 6:41 in when
his rising point shot found the far right upper corner. Joseph had
no chance as he was screened by his own defenseman Danny Markov,
who was chasing a New Jersey forward through the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph came up big 12 minutes into the game when Patrik Elias --
set up by an Alexander Mogilny pass -- blasted a shot off Joseph's
mask. Elias got to the rebound only to have his second shot blocked
by diving defenseman Tomas Kaberle.
</P>
<P>
   Mogilny then got to the loose puck and flipped it at the net,
only to have Joseph stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes into the third, Elias deflected a shot towards the
net but it hit Joseph's toe and off the post.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional point of the night came early in the first when
injured Maple Leafs defenseman Bryan Berard, wearing sunglasses
over his damaged right eye, received a minute-long standing
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a private booth at the game, Berard was shown on the
center-ice video screen, and waved three times to acknowledge the
cheering crowd at Air Canada Centre.
</P>
<P>
   It was Berard's first time at a game since being clipped in the
right eye March 11 by the stick blade of Ottawa forward Marian
Hossa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
