<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Winds Drive Ariz. Forest Fire  </HEADLINE>
By JOLYN OKIMOTO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Firefighters returned to work Saturday on a
wind-driven forest fire after sitting out the night to rest and
avoid dangerous conditions.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, authorities said crews had the blaze 10 percent
contained. However, there was no estimate for full containment
because of high temperatures, low humidity and strong winds.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Killebrew, a fire spokesman for the Tonto National Forest,
said, said 450 firefighters were assigned to the 5,370-acre blaze
along with four airtankers and four helicopters. There were no
reports of injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Little relief from the weather was forecast, with lower
temperatures but continued wind through Sunday, the National
Weather Service said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire didn't immediately threaten any structures and none had
been lost by Saturday, Killebrew said.
</P>
<P>
   The fire started Wednesday in the Sierra Ancha Mountains about
30 miles north of Globe, and campers, workers at the Murphy Ranch
and a Forest Service fire lookout at Aztec Peak were evacuated
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service officials said they believed the fire was of
human origin.
</P>
<P>
   Years of fire suppression had helped build up large amounts of
undergrowth, leaves, pine needles, and twigs in the area, and
winter brought little moisture to the area.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the vegetation has less than 10 percent moisture content
and some has less than 4 percent, Payne said.
</P>
<P>
   ''What you've got is kiln-dried,'' he said. ''It's just like a
tinderbox.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Forest Service Southwest Region: www.fs.fed.us/r3/fire
</P>
</TEXT>
