<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian Air Incident Confirmed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) -- An armed Indonesian military plane
flew within 20 feet of five unarmed Australian air force aircraft,
Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Downer said the Australian pilots were forced to use hand
signals to communicate with the Indonesian pilots during the
interception in international airspace on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred amid continuing allegations of Australian
invasions of Indonesian air space, which have all been denied by
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday morning, four unarmed F/A-18s and one Boeing 707
tanker of the Royal Australian Air Force were en route to Singapore
from Darwin when they were intercepted by two armed Indonesian F-5
aircraft south of West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ''The RAAF believes the (Indonesian) aircraft were armed,''
Downer told Australian television's Nine Network. He said the
Australian planes had Indonesian clearance for their flight.
</P>
<P>
   ''After the F-5 aircraft flew by -- one of them apparently flew
within 20 feet of one of the Australian aircraft -- after this
incident the Australian aircraft continued on their journey across
Indonesia and through to Singapore.''
</P>
<P>
   Downer said he did not believe the Australian planes were
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ''As I understand it, what happened was the two aircraft came up
to meet with the five Australian aircraft and flew alongside
them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Downer said no more action would be taken by Australia over the
incident, which was reported Saturday by the Indonesian newspaper
Kompas.
</P>
<P>
   The incident is the latest irritant in relations between the two
neighbors, which collapsed after Australia led a multinational
peacekeeping force into East Timor last September.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to mend the strained relationship, President
Abdurrahman Wahid on Friday proposed a three-way meeting with Prime
Minister John Howard and East Timorese leader Jose Alexandre
Gusmao.
</P>
</TEXT>
