<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 29, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Vietnam Anniversary Marked With Celebrations
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam (AP) -- Reunification Palace in Ho Chi Minh City
turned from a military parade into spring pageant of everything from floats to
stilt walkers, dragon dancers and child ballet performers Sunday, the
anniversary of the end of the Vietnam War. An estimated 20,000 people watched
goose-stepping soldiers, barefooted minority groups, religious representatives,
including some in black Catholic hassocks, rifle-toting female soldiers in black
pajamas and khaki hats, and women in a rainbow of brightly colored clothes
parade through the palace grounds and past a reviewing stand for 90 minutes.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Thousands March For Elian in Little Havana
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HAVANA (AP) -- Thousands of chanting demonstrators marched peacefully through
Miami's Little Havana today still seething over last week's raid that took Elian
Gonzalez out of the home of his Miami relatives. A counter rally in Cutler
Ridge, in south Miami-Dade County, attracted about 1,500 protesters who
supported the government's actions and criticized the city government shake-up.
They lined the streets and waved American flags as passing cars honked their
horns. No one was arrested. The boy is now living with his father, stepmother
and half brother at the rural Wye River retreat in Maryland. He must remain in
the United States until a federal appeals court rules on the Miami relatives'
bid for him to have an asylum hearing.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Police Probe Death of Waco Expert
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Police said today they are investigating the death of an
expert hired by a congressional committee who alleged last October that shots
were fired in the Waco siege. There was no sign of a break-in or struggle at the
firm of Infrared Technology outside Washington where the badly decomposed body
of Carlos Ghigliotti, 42, was found Friday afternoon, officials said.
Ghigliotti, a thermal imaging analyst hired by the House Government Reform
Committee to review tape of the siege, said he determined the FBI fired shots on
April 19, 1993.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mich. Man Kills Wife, 2 Others, Self
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) -- A man apparently distraught over his wife's
decision to leave him shot and killed her and two others and then killed
himself, authorities said. Raeann Rice, who told family members that her
husband, Michael Rice, had pulled a gun on her several days earlier, returned to
her home about 1:30 p.m. today with her sister and her sister's boyfriend. About
6:15 p.m., members of a special weapons and tactics team looked in a back window
and saw the bodies of Rice and his wife at the bottom of the stairs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report Admonishes Pakistan on Terror
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A State Department report on terrorist activities
worldwide urges Pakistan to curb armed groups fighting India for control of the
disputed territory of Kashmir. Seven countries are on the department's list of
nations that sponsor terrorism: Libya, Syria, Iran, Iraq, Cuba, Sudan and North
Korea. Countries can be added or deleted from the list at any time. While
Pakistan is not on the list, a State Department official said the report notes
that Pakistan is being watched.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ecumenical Patriarch Observes Easter
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- The spiritual leader of the world's Orthodox
Christians celebrated Easter in a candlelit midnight ceremony in Istanbul on
Sunday in front of an unusually large crowd of worshippers -- mostly Greeks
attracted by the recent rapprochement between Turkey and Greece. Bus loads of
Greek faithful filled the patriarchate, on the shore of Istanbul's Golden Horn,
leaving many outside its gates during the procession led by Ecumenical Patriarch
Bartholomew I. Easter, the anniversary of the resurrection of Jesus Christ, is
observed by the world's 200 million Orthodox on Sunday. Roman Catholics and
Protestants celebrate Easter a week earlier.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Devils Beat Maple Leafs 1-0
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Martin Brodeur stopped 20 Toronto shots as the New Jersey
Devils evened their second-round playoff series, which has become a battle of
goalies. Curtis Joseph stopped every shot he saw, but was helplessly screened
when Colin White scored the lone goal Saturday night in New Jersey's 1-0 victory
in Game 2 of the best-of-seven Eastern Conference semifinals. The series
switches to New Jersey for games 3 and 4, Monday and Wednesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Athletics Beat Twins 6-2, 10 innings
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Ben Grieve hit his first career grand slam in the 10th
inning as the Oakland Athletics outlasted Eric Milton and the Minnesota Twins
6-2 on Saturday night. Grieve's fourth homer of the season, off Eddie Guardado,
gave him five RBIs as the A's won for the fourth time in six games. Milton
allowed two hits in eight innings, retiring the A's in order in every inning but
the fifth. He struck out eight and didn't allow a walk for the Twins, who lost
their third straight.
</P>
